# nl-rag distilled facts — domain: object-tracking-cv
# one declarative sentence per line; load with:  neuron --db app.db import pack.facts --scope knowledge
[src:object-tracking-cv/computer-vision] The scientific discipline of computer vision is concerned with the theory behind artificial systems that extract information from images.
[src:object-tracking-cv/computer-vision] Image data can take many forms, such as video sequences, views from multiple cameras, multi-dimensional data from a 3D scanner, 3D point clouds from LiDaR sensors, or medical scanning devices.
[src:object-tracking-cv/computer-vision] The technological discipline of computer vision seeks to apply its theories and models to the construction of computer vision systems.
[src:object-tracking-cv/computer-vision] Subdisciplines of computer vision include scene reconstruction, object detection, event detection, activity recognition, video tracking, object recognition, 3D pose estimation, learning, indexing, motion estimation, visual servoing, 3D scene modeling, and image restoration.
[src:object-tracking-cv/computer-vision] Computer vision is an interdisciplinary field that deals with how computers can be made to gain high-level understanding from digital images or videos.
[src:object-tracking-cv/computer-vision] From the perspective of engineering, it seeks to automate tasks that the human visual system can do.
[src:object-tracking-cv/computer-vision] "Computer vision is concerned with the automatic extraction, analysis, and understanding of useful information from a single image or a sequence of images.
[src:object-tracking-cv/computer-vision] It involves the development of a theoretical and algorithmic basis to achieve automatic visual understanding." As a scientific discipline, computer vision is concerned with the theory behind artificial systems that extract information from images.
[src:object-tracking-cv/computer-vision] The image data can take many forms, such as video sequences, views from multiple cameras, or multi-dimensional data from a medical scanner.
[src:object-tracking-cv/computer-vision] As a technological discipline, computer vision seeks to apply its theories and models for the construction of computer vision systems.
[src:object-tracking-cv/computer-vision] Machine vision refers to a systems engineering discipline, especially in the context of factory automation.
[src:object-tracking-cv/computer-vision] In more recent times, the terms computer vision and machine vision have converged to a greater degree.
[src:object-tracking-cv/computer-vision] In the late 1960s, computer vision began at universities that were pioneering artificial intelligence.
[src:object-tracking-cv/computer-vision] It was meant to mimic the human visual system as a stepping stone to endowing robots with intelligent behavior.
[src:object-tracking-cv/computer-vision] In 1966, it was believed that this could be achieved through an undergraduate summer project, by attaching a camera to a computer and having it "describe what it saw".
[src:object-tracking-cv/computer-vision] What distinguished computer vision from the prevalent field of digital image processing at that time was a desire to extract three-dimensional structure from images with the goal of achieving full scene understanding.
[src:object-tracking-cv/computer-vision] The next decade saw studies based on more rigorous mathematical analysis and quantitative aspects of computer vision.
[src:object-tracking-cv/computer-vision] These include the concept of scale-space, the inference of shape from various cues such as shading, texture and focus, and contour models known as snakes.
[src:object-tracking-cv/computer-vision] Researchers also realized that many of these mathematical concepts could be treated within the same optimization framework as regularization and Markov random fields.
[src:object-tracking-cv/computer-vision] By the 1990s, some of the previous research topics became more active than others.
[src:object-tracking-cv/computer-vision] Research in projective 3-D reconstructions led to better understanding of camera calibration.
[src:object-tracking-cv/computer-vision] With the advent of optimization methods for camera calibration, it was realized that a lot of the ideas were already explored in bundle adjustment theory from the field of photogrammetry.
[src:object-tracking-cv/computer-vision] This led to methods for sparse 3-D reconstructions of scenes from multiple images.
[src:object-tracking-cv/computer-vision] Progress was made on the dense stereo correspondence problem and further multi-view stereo techniques.
[src:object-tracking-cv/computer-vision] At the same time, variations of graph cut were used to solve image segmentation.
[src:object-tracking-cv/computer-vision] This decade also marked the first time statistical learning techniques were used in practice to recognize faces in images (see Eigenface).
[src:object-tracking-cv/computer-vision] Toward the end of the 1990s, a significant change came about with the increased interaction between the fields of computer graphics and computer vision.
[src:object-tracking-cv/computer-vision] This included image-based rendering, image morphing, view interpolation, panoramic image stitching and early light-field rendering.
[src:object-tracking-cv/computer-vision] Recent work has seen the resurgence of feature-based methods used in conjunction with machine learning techniques and complex optimization frameworks.
[src:object-tracking-cv/computer-vision] The advancement of Deep Learning techniques has brought further life to the field of computer vision.
[src:object-tracking-cv/computer-vision] The accuracy of deep learning algorithms on several benchmark computer vision data sets for tasks ranging from classification, segmentation and optical flow has surpassed prior methods.
[src:object-tracking-cv/computer-vision] Solid-state physics is another field that is closely related to computer vision.
[src:object-tracking-cv/computer-vision] Most computer vision systems rely on image sensors, which detect electromagnetic radiation, which is typically in the form of either visible, infrared or ultraviolet light.
[src:object-tracking-cv/computer-vision] The sensors are designed using quantum physics.
[src:object-tracking-cv/computer-vision] The process by which light interacts with surfaces is explained using physics.
[src:object-tracking-cv/computer-vision] Physics explains the behavior of optics which are a core part of most imaging systems.
[src:object-tracking-cv/computer-vision] Sophisticated image sensors even require quantum mechanics to provide a complete understanding of the image formation process.
[src:object-tracking-cv/computer-vision] Also, various measurement problems in physics can be addressed using computer vision, for example, motion in fluids.
[src:object-tracking-cv/computer-vision] The starfish match with a ringed texture and a star outline, whereas most sea urchins match with a striped texture and oval shape.
[src:object-tracking-cv/computer-vision] However, the instance of a ring-textured sea urchin creates a weakly weighted association between them.
[src:object-tracking-cv/computer-vision] The network correctly detects the starfish.
[src:object-tracking-cv/computer-vision] However, the weakly weighted association between ringed texture and sea urchin also confers a weak signal to the latter from one of two intermediate nodes.
[src:object-tracking-cv/computer-vision] In addition, a shell that was not included in the training gives a weak signal for the oval shape, also resulting in a weak signal for the sea urchin output.
[src:object-tracking-cv/computer-vision] In reality, textures and outlines would not be represented by single nodes, but rather by associated weight patterns of multiple nodes.
[src:object-tracking-cv/computer-vision] Neurobiology has greatly influenced the development of computer vision algorithms.
[src:object-tracking-cv/computer-vision] Over the last century, there has been an extensive study of eyes, neurons, and brain structures devoted to the processing of visual stimuli in both humans and various animals.
[src:object-tracking-cv/computer-vision] This has led to a coarse yet convoluted description of how natural vision systems operate in order to solve certain vision-related tasks.
[src:object-tracking-cv/computer-vision] These results have led to a sub-field within computer vision where artificial systems are designed to mimic the processing and behavior of biological systems at different levels of complexity.
[src:object-tracking-cv/computer-vision] Also, some of the learning-based methods developed within computer vision (*e.g.* neural net and deep learning based image and feature analysis and classification) have their background in neurobiology.
[src:object-tracking-cv/computer-vision] The Neocognitron, a neural network developed in the 1970s by Kunihiko Fukushima, is an early example of computer vision taking direct inspiration from neurobiology, specifically the primary visual cortex.
[src:object-tracking-cv/computer-vision] Some strands of computer vision research are closely related to the study of biological vision—indeed, just as many strands of AI research are closely tied with research into human intelligence and the use of stored knowledge to interpret, integrate, and utilize visual information.
[src:object-tracking-cv/computer-vision] The field of biological vision studies and models the physiological processes behind visual perception in humans and other animals.
[src:object-tracking-cv/computer-vision] Computer vision, on the other hand, develops and describes the algorithms implemented in software and hardware behind artificial vision systems.
[src:object-tracking-cv/computer-vision] An interdisciplinary exchange between biological and computer vision has proven fruitful for both fields.
[src:object-tracking-cv/computer-vision] Yet another field related to computer vision is signal processing.
[src:object-tracking-cv/computer-vision] Many methods for processing one-variable signals, typically temporal signals, can be extended in a natural way to the processing of two-variable signals or multi-variable signals in computer vision.
[src:object-tracking-cv/computer-vision] However, because of the specific nature of images, there are many methods developed within computer vision that have no counterpart in the processing of one-variable signals.
[src:object-tracking-cv/computer-vision] Together with the multi-dimensionality of the signal, this defines a subfield in signal processing as a part of computer vision.
[src:object-tracking-cv/computer-vision] Robot navigation sometimes deals with autonomous path planning or deliberation for robotic systems to navigate through an environment.
[src:object-tracking-cv/computer-vision] A detailed understanding of these environments is required to navigate through them.
[src:object-tracking-cv/computer-vision] Visual computing is a generic term for all computer science disciplines dealing with images and 3D models, such as computer graphics, image processing, visualization, computer vision, virtual and augmented reality, video processing, and computational visualistics.
[src:object-tracking-cv/computer-vision] Visual computing also includes aspects of pattern recognition, human computer interaction, machine learning and digital libraries.
[src:object-tracking-cv/computer-vision] The core challenges are the acquisition, processing, analysis and rendering of visual information (mainly images and video).
[src:object-tracking-cv/computer-vision] Application areas include industrial quality control, medical image processing and visualization, surveying, robotics, multimedia systems, virtual heritage, special effects in movies and television, and ludology.
[src:object-tracking-cv/computer-vision] Visual computing also includes digital art and digital media studies.
[src:object-tracking-cv/computer-vision] Besides the above-mentioned views on computer vision, many of the related research topics can also be studied from a purely mathematical point of view.
[src:object-tracking-cv/computer-vision] For example, many methods in computer vision are based on statistics, optimization or geometry.
[src:object-tracking-cv/computer-vision] Finally, a significant part of the field is devoted to the implementation aspect of computer vision; how existing methods can be realized in various combinations of software and hardware, or how these methods can be modified in order to gain processing speed without losing too much performance.
[src:object-tracking-cv/computer-vision] Computer vision is also used in fashion eCommerce, inventory management, patent search, furniture, and the beauty industry.
[src:object-tracking-cv/computer-vision] The fields most closely related to computer vision are image processing, image analysis and machine vision.
[src:object-tracking-cv/computer-vision] There is a significant overlap in the range of techniques and applications that these cover.
[src:object-tracking-cv/computer-vision] This implies that the basic techniques that are used and developed in these fields are similar, something which can be interpreted as there is only one field with different names.
[src:object-tracking-cv/computer-vision] In image processing, the input and output are both images, whereas in computer vision, the input is an image or video, and the output could be an enhanced image, an analysis of the image's content, or even a system's behavior based on that analysis.
[src:object-tracking-cv/computer-vision] Computer graphics produces image data from 3D models, and computer vision often produces 3D models from image data.
[src:object-tracking-cv/computer-vision] There is also a trend towards a combination of the two disciplines, *e.g.*, as explored in augmented reality.
[src:object-tracking-cv/computer-vision] Photogrammetry also overlaps with computer vision, e.g., stereophotogrammetry vs. computer stereo vision.
[src:object-tracking-cv/computer-vision] Applications range from tasks such as industrial machine vision systems which, say, inspect bottles speeding by on a production line, to research into artificial intelligence and computers or robots that can comprehend the world around them.
[src:object-tracking-cv/computer-vision] The computer vision and machine vision fields have significant overlap.
[src:object-tracking-cv/computer-vision] Computer vision covers the core technology of automated image analysis which is used in many fields.
[src:object-tracking-cv/computer-vision] Machine vision usually refers to a process of combining automated image analysis with other methods and technologies to provide automated inspection and robot guidance in industrial applications.
[src:object-tracking-cv/computer-vision] In many computer-vision applications, computers are pre-programmed to solve a particular task, but methods based on learning are now becoming increasingly common.
[src:object-tracking-cv/computer-vision] For 2024, the leading areas of computer vision were industry (market size US$5.22 billion), medicine (market size US$2.6 billion), military (market size US$996.2 million).
[src:object-tracking-cv/computer-vision] One of the most prominent application fields is medical computer vision, or medical image processing, characterized by the extraction of information from image data to diagnose a patient.
[src:object-tracking-cv/computer-vision] An example of this is the detection of tumours, arteriosclerosis or other malign changes, and a variety of dental pathologies; measurements of organ dimensions, blood flow, etc. are another example.
[src:object-tracking-cv/computer-vision] It also supports medical research by providing new information: *e.g.*, about the structure of the brain or the quality of medical treatments.
[src:object-tracking-cv/computer-vision] Applications of computer vision in the medical area also include enhancement of images interpreted by humans—ultrasonic images or X-ray images, for example—to reduce the influence of noise.
[src:object-tracking-cv/computer-vision] A second application area in computer vision is in industry, sometimes called machine vision, where information is extracted for the purpose of supporting a production process.
[src:object-tracking-cv/computer-vision] One example is quality control where details or final products are being automatically inspected in order to find defects.
[src:object-tracking-cv/computer-vision] One of the most prevalent fields for such inspecti is the Wafer industry in which every single Wafer is being measured and inspected for inaccuracies or defects to prevent a computer chip from coming to market in an unusable manner.
[src:object-tracking-cv/computer-vision] Another example is a measurement of the position and orientation of details to be picked up by a robot arm.
[src:object-tracking-cv/computer-vision] Machine vision is also heavily used in the agricultural processes to remove undesirable foodstuff from bulk material, a process called optical sorting.
[src:object-tracking-cv/computer-vision] The obvious examples are the detection of enemy soldiers or vehicles and missile guidance.
[src:object-tracking-cv/computer-vision] More advanced systems for missile guidance send the missile to an area rather than a specific target, and target selection is made when the missile reaches the area based on locally acquired image data.
[src:object-tracking-cv/computer-vision] Modern military concepts, such as "battlefield awareness", imply that various sensors, including image sensors, provide a rich set of information about a combat scene that can be used to support strategic decisions.
[src:object-tracking-cv/computer-vision] In this case, automatic processing of the data is used to reduce complexity and to fuse information from multiple sensors to increase reliability.
[src:object-tracking-cv/computer-vision] One of the newer application areas is autonomous vehicles, which include submersibles, land-based vehicles (small robots with wheels, cars, or trucks), aerial vehicles, and unmanned aerial vehicles (UAV).
[src:object-tracking-cv/computer-vision] The level of autonomy ranges from fully autonomous (unmanned) vehicles to vehicles where computer-vision-based systems support a driver or a pilot in various situations.
[src:object-tracking-cv/computer-vision] Fully autonomous vehicles typically use computer vision for navigation, e.g., for knowing where they are or mapping their environment (SLAM), for detecting obstacles.
[src:object-tracking-cv/computer-vision] It can also be used for detecting certain task-specific events, *e.g.*, a UAV looking for forest fires.
[src:object-tracking-cv/computer-vision] Examples of supporting systems are obstacle warning systems in cars, cameras and LiDAR sensors in vehicles, and systems for autonomous landing of aircraft.
[src:object-tracking-cv/computer-vision] Several car manufacturers have demonstrated systems for autonomous driving of cars.
[src:object-tracking-cv/computer-vision] There are ample examples of military autonomous vehicles ranging from advanced missiles to UAVs for recon missions or missile guidance.
[src:object-tracking-cv/computer-vision] Space exploration is already being made with autonomous vehicles using computer vision, *e.g.*, NASA's *Curiosity* and CNSA's *Yutu-2* rover.
[src:object-tracking-cv/computer-vision] Materials such as rubber and silicon are being used to create sensors that allow for applications such as detecting microundulations and calibrating robotic hands.
[src:object-tracking-cv/computer-vision] Rubber can be used in order to create a mold that can be placed over a finger, inside of this mold would be multiple strain gauges.
[src:object-tracking-cv/computer-vision] The finger mold and sensors could then be placed on top of a small sheet of rubber containing an array of rubber pins.
[src:object-tracking-cv/computer-vision] A user can then wear the finger mold and trace a surface.
[src:object-tracking-cv/computer-vision] A computer can then read the data from the strain gauges and measure if one or more of the pins are being pushed upward.
[src:object-tracking-cv/computer-vision] If a pin is being pushed upward then the computer can recognize this as an imperfection in the surface.
[src:object-tracking-cv/computer-vision] This sort of technology is useful in order to receive accurate data on imperfections on a very large surface.
[src:object-tracking-cv/computer-vision] Another variation of this finger mold sensor are sensors that contain a camera suspended in silicon.
[src:object-tracking-cv/computer-vision] The silicon forms a dome around the outside of the camera and embedded in the silicon are point markers that are equally spaced.
[src:object-tracking-cv/computer-vision] These cameras can then be placed on devices such as robotic hands in order to allow the computer to receive highly accurate tactile data.
[src:object-tracking-cv/computer-vision] Each of the application areas described above employ a range of computer vision tasks; more or less well-defined measurement problems or processing problems, which can be solved using a variety of methods.
[src:object-tracking-cv/computer-vision] Some examples of typical computer vision tasks are presented below.
[src:object-tracking-cv/computer-vision] Computer vision tasks include methods for acquiring, processing, analyzing and understanding digital images, and extraction of high-dimensional data from the real world in order to produce numerical or symbolic information, *e.g.*, in the forms of decisions.
[src:object-tracking-cv/computer-vision] Understanding in this context means the transformation of visual images into descriptions of the world that can interface with other thought processes and elicit appropriate action.
[src:object-tracking-cv/computer-vision] This image understanding can be seen as the disentangling of symbolic information from image data using models constructed with the aid of geometry, physics, statistics, and learning theory.
[src:object-tracking-cv/computer-vision] The classical problem in computer vision, image processing, and machine vision is that of determining whether or not the image data contains some specific object, feature, or activity.
[src:object-tracking-cv/computer-vision] Different varieties of recognition problem are described in the literature.
[src:object-tracking-cv/computer-vision] Currently, the best algorithms for such tasks are based on convolutional neural networks.
[src:object-tracking-cv/computer-vision] An illustration of their capabilities is given by the ImageNet Large Scale Visual Recognition Challenge; this is a benchmark in object classification and detection, with millions of images and 1000 object classes used in the competition.
[src:object-tracking-cv/computer-vision] Performance of convolutional neural networks on the ImageNet tests is now close to that of humans.
[src:object-tracking-cv/computer-vision] The best algorithms still struggle with objects that are small or thin, such as a small ant on the stem of a flower or a person holding a quill in their hand.
[src:object-tracking-cv/computer-vision] They also have trouble with images that have been distorted with filters (an increasingly common phenomenon with modern digital cameras).
[src:object-tracking-cv/computer-vision] By contrast, those kinds of images rarely trouble humans.
[src:object-tracking-cv/computer-vision] Humans, however, tend to have trouble with other issues.
[src:object-tracking-cv/computer-vision] For example, they are not good at classifying objects into fine-grained classes, such as the particular breed of dog or species of bird, whereas convolutional neural networks handle this with ease.
[src:object-tracking-cv/computer-vision] Several tasks relate to motion estimation, where an image sequence is processed to produce an estimate of the velocity either at each points in the image or in the 3D scene or even of the camera that produces the images.
[src:object-tracking-cv/computer-vision] Given one or (typically) more images of a scene, or a video, scene reconstruction aims at computing a 3D model of the scene.
[src:object-tracking-cv/computer-vision] In the simplest case, the model can be a set of 3D points.
[src:object-tracking-cv/computer-vision] More sophisticated methods produce a complete 3D surface model.
[src:object-tracking-cv/computer-vision] The advent of 3D imaging not requiring motion or scanning, and related processing algorithms is enabling rapid advances in this field.
[src:object-tracking-cv/computer-vision] Grid-based 3D sensing can be used to acquire 3D images from multiple angles.
[src:object-tracking-cv/computer-vision] Algorithms are now available to stitch multiple 3D images together into point clouds and 3D models.
[src:object-tracking-cv/computer-vision] Image restoration comes into the picture when the original image is degraded or damaged due to some external factors like lens wrong positioning, transmission interference, low lighting or motion blurs, etc., which is referred to as noise.
[src:object-tracking-cv/computer-vision] When the images are degraded or damaged, the information to be extracted from them also gets damaged.
[src:object-tracking-cv/computer-vision] Therefore, we need to recover or restore the image as it was intended to be.
[src:object-tracking-cv/computer-vision] The aim of image restoration is the removal of noise (sensor noise, motion blur, etc.) from images.
[src:object-tracking-cv/computer-vision] The simplest possible approach for noise removal is various types of filters, such as low-pass filters or median filters.
[src:object-tracking-cv/computer-vision] More sophisticated methods assume a model of how the local image structures look to distinguish them from noise.
[src:object-tracking-cv/computer-vision] By first analyzing the image data in terms of the local image structures, such as lines or edges, and then controlling the filtering based on local information from the analysis step, a better level of noise removal is usually obtained compared to the simpler approaches.
[src:object-tracking-cv/computer-vision] The organization of a computer vision system is highly application-dependent.
[src:object-tracking-cv/computer-vision] Some systems are stand-alone applications that solve a specific measurement or detection problem, while others constitute a sub-system of a larger design which, for example, also contains sub-systems for control of mechanical actuators, planning, information databases, man-machine interfaces, etc.
[src:object-tracking-cv/computer-vision] The specific implementation of a computer vision system also depends on whether its functionality is pre-specified or if some part of it can be learned or modified during operation.
[src:object-tracking-cv/computer-vision] Many functions are unique to the application.
[src:object-tracking-cv/computer-vision] There are, however, typical functions that are found in many computer vision systems.
[src:object-tracking-cv/computer-vision] More complex features may be related to texture, shape, or motion.
[src:object-tracking-cv/computer-vision] Image-understanding systems (IUS) include three levels of abstraction as follows: low level includes image primitives such as edges, texture elements, or regions; intermediate level includes boundaries, surfaces and volumes; and high level includes objects, scenes, or events.
[src:object-tracking-cv/computer-vision] Many of these requirements are entirely topics for further research.
[src:object-tracking-cv/computer-vision] The representational requirements in the designing of IUS for these levels are: representation of prototypical concepts, concept organization, spatial knowledge, temporal knowledge, scaling, and description by comparison and differentiation.
[src:object-tracking-cv/computer-vision] While inference refers to the process of deriving new, not explicitly represented facts from currently known facts, control refers to the process that selects which of the many inference, search, and matching techniques should be applied at a particular stage of processing.
[src:object-tracking-cv/computer-vision] Inference and control requirements for IUS are: search and hypothesis activation, matching and hypothesis testing, generation and use of expectations, change and focus of attention, certainty and strength of belief, inference and goal satisfaction.
[src:object-tracking-cv/computer-vision] There are many kinds of computer vision systems; however, all of them contain these basic elements: a power source, at least one image acquisition device (camera, ccd, etc.), a processor, and control and communication cables or some kind of wireless interconnection mechanism.
[src:object-tracking-cv/computer-vision] In addition, a practical vision system contains software, as well as a display in order to monitor the system.
[src:object-tracking-cv/computer-vision] Vision systems for inner spaces, as most industrial ones, contain an illumination system and may be placed in a controlled environment.
[src:object-tracking-cv/computer-vision] Furthermore, a completed system includes many accessories, such as camera supports, cables, and connectors.
[src:object-tracking-cv/computer-vision] Most computer vision systems use visible-light cameras passively viewing a scene at frame rates of at most 60 frames per second (usually far slower).
[src:object-tracking-cv/computer-vision] Such hardware captures "images" that are then processed often using the same computer vision algorithms used to process visible-light images.
[src:object-tracking-cv/computer-vision] For applications in robotics, fast, real-time video systems are critically important and often can simplify the processing needed for certain algorithms.
[src:object-tracking-cv/computer-vision] When combined with a high-speed projector, fast image acquisition allows 3D measurement and feature tracking to be realized.
[src:object-tracking-cv/computer-vision] Egocentric vision systems are composed of a wearable camera that automatically take pictures from a first-person perspective.
[src:object-tracking-cv/computer-vision] As of 2016, vision processing units are emerging as a new class of processors to complement CPUs and graphics processing units (GPUs) in this role.
[src:object-tracking-cv/kalman-filter-p01] The filter is constructed as a mean squared error minimiser, but an alternative derivation of the filter is also provided showing how the filter relates to maximum likelihood statistics.
[src:object-tracking-cv/kalman-filter-p01] Kalman filtering has numerous technological applications.
[src:object-tracking-cv/kalman-filter-p01] A common application is for guidance, navigation, and control of vehicles, particularly aircraft, spacecraft and ships positioned dynamically.
[src:object-tracking-cv/kalman-filter-p01] Furthermore, Kalman filtering is much applied in time series analysis tasks such as signal processing and econometrics.
[src:object-tracking-cv/kalman-filter-p01] Kalman filtering is also important for robotic motion planning and control, and can be used for trajectory optimization.
[src:object-tracking-cv/kalman-filter-p01] Kalman filtering also works for modeling the central nervous system's control of movement.
[src:object-tracking-cv/kalman-filter-p01] Due to the time delay between issuing motor commands and receiving sensory feedback, the use of Kalman filters provides a realistic model for making estimates of the current state of a motor system and issuing updated commands.
[src:object-tracking-cv/kalman-filter-p01] The algorithm works via a two-phase process: a *prediction phase* and an *update phase*.
[src:object-tracking-cv/kalman-filter-p01] In the prediction phase, the Kalman filter produces estimates of the current state variables, including their uncertainties.
[src:object-tracking-cv/kalman-filter-p01] Once the outcome of the next measurement (necessarily corrupted with some error, including random noise) is observed, these estimates are updated using a weighted average, with more weight given to estimates with greater certainty.
[src:object-tracking-cv/kalman-filter-p01] It can operate in real time, using only the present input measurements and the state calculated previously and its uncertainty matrix; no additional past information is required.
[src:object-tracking-cv/kalman-filter-p01] Optimality of Kalman filtering assumes that errors have a normal (Gaussian) distribution.
[src:object-tracking-cv/kalman-filter-p01] Kálmán, "The following assumptions are made about random processes: Physical random phenomena may be thought of as due to primary random sources exciting dynamic systems.
[src:object-tracking-cv/kalman-filter-p01] It is a common misconception (perpetuated in the literature) that the Kalman filter cannot be rigorously applied unless all noise processes are assumed to be Gaussian.
[src:object-tracking-cv/kalman-filter-p01] Extensions and generalizations of the method have also been developed, such as the extended Kalman filter and the unscented Kalman filter which work on nonlinear systems.
[src:object-tracking-cv/kalman-filter-p01] The basis is a hidden Markov model such that the state space of the latent variables is continuous and all latent and observed variables have Gaussian distributions.
[src:object-tracking-cv/kalman-filter-p01] Kalman filtering has been used successfully in multi-sensor fusion, and distributed sensor networks to develop distributed or consensus Kalman filtering.
[src:object-tracking-cv/kalman-filter-p01] The filtering method is named for Hungarian émigré Rudolf E.
[src:object-tracking-cv/kalman-filter-p01] Kálmán, although Thorvald Nicolai Thiele and Peter Swerling developed a similar algorithm earlier.
[src:object-tracking-cv/kalman-filter-p01] Bucy of the Johns Hopkins Applied Physics Laboratory contributed to the theory, causing it to be known sometimes as Kalman–Bucy filtering.
[src:object-tracking-cv/kalman-filter-p01] Kalman was inspired to derive the Kalman filter by applying state variables to the Wiener filtering problem.
[src:object-tracking-cv/kalman-filter-p01] Schmidt is generally credited with developing the first implementation of a Kalman filter.
[src:object-tracking-cv/kalman-filter-p01] He realized that the filter could be divided into two distinct parts, with one part for time periods between sensor outputs and another part for incorporating measurements.
[src:object-tracking-cv/kalman-filter-p01] It was during a visit by Kálmán to the NASA Ames Research Center that Schmidt saw the applicability of Kálmán's ideas to the nonlinear problem of trajectory estimation for the Apollo program resulting in its incorporation in the Apollo navigation computer.
[src:object-tracking-cv/kalman-filter-p01] This digital filter is sometimes termed the *Stratonovich–Kalman–Bucy filter* because it is a special case of a more general, nonlinear filter developed by the Soviet mathematician Ruslan Stratonovich.
[src:object-tracking-cv/kalman-filter-p01] In fact, some of the special case linear filter's equations appeared in papers by Stratonovich that were published before the summer of 1961, when Kalman met with Stratonovich during a conference in Moscow.
[src:object-tracking-cv/kalman-filter-p01] This Kalman filtering was first described and developed partially in technical papers by Swerling (1958), Kalman (1960) and Kalman and Bucy (1961).
[src:object-tracking-cv/kalman-filter-p01] Kalman filters have been vital in the implementation of the navigation systems of U.S.
[src:object-tracking-cv/kalman-filter-p01] Navy nuclear ballistic missile submarines, and in the guidance and navigation systems of cruise missiles such as the U.S.
[src:object-tracking-cv/kalman-filter-p01] Air Force's Air Launched Cruise Missile.
[src:object-tracking-cv/kalman-filter-p01] They are also used in the guidance and navigation systems of reusable launch vehicles and the attitude control and navigation systems of spacecraft which dock at the International Space Station.
[src:object-tracking-cv/kalman-filter-p01] As such, it is a common sensor fusion and data fusion algorithm.
[src:object-tracking-cv/kalman-filter-p01] Noisy sensor data, approximations in the equations that describe the system evolution, and external factors that are not accounted for, all limit how well it is possible to determine the system's state.
[src:object-tracking-cv/kalman-filter-p01] The Kalman filter deals effectively with the uncertainty due to noisy sensor data and, to some extent, with random external factors.
[src:object-tracking-cv/kalman-filter-p01] The Kalman filter produces an estimate of the state of the system as an average of the system's predicted state and of the new measurement using a weighted average.
[src:object-tracking-cv/kalman-filter-p01] The purpose of the weights is that values with better (i.e., smaller) estimated uncertainty are "trusted" more.
[src:object-tracking-cv/kalman-filter-p01] The weights are calculated from the covariance, a measure of the estimated uncertainty of the prediction of the system's state.
[src:object-tracking-cv/kalman-filter-p01] The result of the weighted average is a new state estimate that lies between the predicted and measured state, and has a better estimated uncertainty than either alone.
[src:object-tracking-cv/kalman-filter-p01] This process is repeated at every time step, with the new estimate and its covariance informing the prediction used in the following iteration.
[src:object-tracking-cv/kalman-filter-p01] This means that Kalman filter works recursively and requires only the last "best guess", rather than the entire history, of a system's state to calculate a new state.
[src:object-tracking-cv/kalman-filter-p01] The measurements' certainty-grading and current-state estimate are important considerations.
[src:object-tracking-cv/kalman-filter-p01] It is common to discuss the filter's response in terms of the Kalman filter's *gain*.
[src:object-tracking-cv/kalman-filter-p01] The Kalman gain is the weight given to the measurements and current-state estimate, and can be "tuned" to achieve a particular performance.
[src:object-tracking-cv/kalman-filter-p01] With a high gain, the filter places more weight on the most recent measurements, and thus conforms to them more responsively.
[src:object-tracking-cv/kalman-filter-p01] With a low gain, the filter conforms to the model predictions more closely.
[src:object-tracking-cv/kalman-filter-p01] At the extremes, a high gain (close to one) will result in a more jumpy estimated trajectory, while a low gain (close to zero) will smooth out noise but decrease the responsiveness.
[src:object-tracking-cv/kalman-filter-p01] When performing the actual calculations for the filter (as discussed below), the state estimate and covariances are coded into matrices because of the multiple dimensions involved in a single set of calculations.
[src:object-tracking-cv/kalman-filter-p01] This allows for a representation of linear relationships between different state variables (such as position, velocity, and acceleration) in any of the transition models or covariances.
[src:object-tracking-cv/kalman-filter-p01] As an example application, consider the problem of determining the precise location of a truck.
[src:object-tracking-cv/kalman-filter-p01] The truck can be equipped with a GPS unit that provides an estimate of the position within a few meters.
[src:object-tracking-cv/kalman-filter-p01] The GPS estimate is likely to be noisy; readings 'jump around' rapidly, though remaining within a few meters of the real position.
[src:object-tracking-cv/kalman-filter-p01] In addition, since the truck is expected to follow the laws of physics, its position can also be estimated by integrating its velocity over time, determined by keeping track of wheel revolutions and the angle of the steering wheel.
[src:object-tracking-cv/kalman-filter-p01] This is a technique known as dead reckoning.
[src:object-tracking-cv/kalman-filter-p01] Typically, the dead reckoning will provide a very smooth estimate of the truck's position, but it will drift over time as small errors accumulate.
[src:object-tracking-cv/kalman-filter-p01] For this example, the Kalman filter can be thought of as operating in two distinct phases: predict and update.
[src:object-tracking-cv/kalman-filter-p01] In the prediction phase, the truck's old position will be modified according to the physical laws of motion (the dynamic or "state transition" model).
[src:object-tracking-cv/kalman-filter-p01] Not only will a new position estimate be calculated, but also a new covariance will be calculated as well.
[src:object-tracking-cv/kalman-filter-p01] Perhaps the covariance is proportional to the speed of the truck because we are more uncertain about the accuracy of the dead reckoning position estimate at high speeds but very certain about the position estimate at low speeds.
[src:object-tracking-cv/kalman-filter-p01] Next, in the update phase, a measurement of the truck's position is taken from the GPS unit.
[src:object-tracking-cv/kalman-filter-p01] Along with this measurement comes some amount of uncertainty, and its covariance relative to that of the prediction from the previous phase determines how much the new measurement will affect the updated prediction.
[src:object-tracking-cv/kalman-filter-p01] Ideally, as the dead reckoning estimates tend to drift away from the real position, the GPS measurement should pull the position estimate back toward the real position but not disturb it to the point of becoming noisy and rapidly jumping.
[src:object-tracking-cv/kalman-filter-p01] The Kalman filter is an efficient recursive filter estimating the internal state of a linear dynamic system from a series of noisy measurements.
[src:object-tracking-cv/kalman-filter-p01] It is used in a wide range of engineering and econometric applications from radar and computer vision to estimation of structural macroeconomic models, and is an important topic in control theory and control systems engineering.
[src:object-tracking-cv/kalman-filter-p01] Together with the linear-quadratic regulator (LQR), the Kalman filter solves the linear–quadratic–Gaussian control problem (LQG).
[src:object-tracking-cv/kalman-filter-p01] The Kalman filter, the linear-quadratic regulator, and the linear–quadratic–Gaussian controller are solutions to what arguably are the most fundamental problems of control theory.
[src:object-tracking-cv/kalman-filter-p01] In most applications, the internal state is much larger (has more degrees of freedom) than the few "observable" parameters which are measured.
[src:object-tracking-cv/kalman-filter-p01] However, by combining a series of measurements, the Kalman filter can estimate the entire internal state.
[src:object-tracking-cv/kalman-filter-p01] For the Dempster–Shafer theory, each state equation or observation is considered a special case of a linear belief function and the Kalman filtering is a special case of combining linear belief functions on a join-tree or Markov tree.
[src:object-tracking-cv/kalman-filter-p01] Additional methods include belief filtering which use Bayes or evidential updates to the state equations.
[src:object-tracking-cv/kalman-filter-p01] A wide variety of Kalman filters exists by now: Kalman's original formulation - now termed the "simple" Kalman filter, the Kalman–Bucy filter, Schmidt's "extended" filter, the information filter, and a variety of "square-root" filters that were developed by Bierman, Thornton, and many others.
[src:object-tracking-cv/kalman-filter-p01] Kalman filtering is based on linear dynamic systems discretized in the time domain.
[src:object-tracking-cv/kalman-filter-p01] They are modeled on a Markov chain built on linear operators perturbed by errors that may include Gaussian noise.
[src:object-tracking-cv/kalman-filter-p01] The state of the target system refers to the ground truth (yet hidden) system configuration of interest, which is represented as a vector of real numbers.
[src:object-tracking-cv/kalman-filter-p01] At each discrete time increment, a linear operator is applied to the state to generate the new state, with some noise mixed in, and optionally some information from the controls on the system if they are known.
[src:object-tracking-cv/kalman-filter-p01] Then, another linear operator mixed with more noise generates the measurable outputs (i.e., observation) from the true ("hidden") state.
[src:object-tracking-cv/kalman-filter-p01] The Kalman filter may be regarded as analogous to the hidden Markov model, with the difference that the hidden state variables have values in a continuous space as opposed to a discrete state space as for the hidden Markov model.
[src:object-tracking-cv/kalman-filter-p01] There is a strong analogy between the equations of a Kalman Filter and those of the hidden Markov model.
[src:object-tracking-cv/kalman-filter-p01] A review of this and other models is given in Roweis and Ghahramani (1999) and Hamilton (1994), Chapter 13.
[src:object-tracking-cv/kalman-filter-p01] In order to use the Kalman filter to estimate the internal state of a process given only a sequence of noisy observations, one must model the process in accordance with the following framework.
[src:object-tracking-cv/kalman-filter-p01] As seen below, it is common in many applications that the matrices $\mathbf {F}$ , $\mathbf {H}$ , $\mathbf {Q}$ , $\mathbf {R}$ , and $\mathbf {B}$ are constant across time, in which case their k index may be dropped.
[src:object-tracking-cv/kalman-filter-p01] If $\mathbf {Q}$ is independent of time, one may, following Roweis and Ghahramani, write $\mathbf {w} _{\bullet }$ instead of $\mathbf {w} _{k}$ to emphasize that the noise has no explicit knowledge of time.
[src:object-tracking-cv/kalman-filter-p01] Analogously to the situation for $\mathbf {w} _{k}$ , one may write $\mathbf {v} _{\bullet }$ instead of $\mathbf {v} _{k}$ if $\mathbf {R}$ is independent of time.
[src:object-tracking-cv/kalman-filter-p01] The initial state, and the noise vectors at each step $\{\mathbf {x} _{0},\mathbf {w} _{1},\dots ,\mathbf {w} _{k},\mathbf {v} _{1},\dots ,\mathbf {v} _{k}\}$ are all assumed to be mutually independent.
[src:object-tracking-cv/kalman-filter-p01] Many real-time dynamic systems do not exactly conform to this model.
[src:object-tracking-cv/kalman-filter-p01] In fact, unmodeled dynamics can seriously degrade the filter performance, even when it was supposed to work with unknown stochastic signals as inputs.
[src:object-tracking-cv/kalman-filter-p01] The reason for this is that the effect of unmodeled dynamics depends on the input, and, therefore, can bring the estimation algorithm to instability (it diverges).
[src:object-tracking-cv/kalman-filter-p01] On the other hand, independent white noise signals will not make the algorithm diverge.
[src:object-tracking-cv/kalman-filter-p01] The problem of distinguishing between measurement noise and unmodeled dynamics is a difficult one and is treated as a problem of control theory using robust control.
[src:object-tracking-cv/kalman-filter-p01] The Kalman filter is a recursive estimator.
[src:object-tracking-cv/kalman-filter-p01] This means that only the estimated state from the previous time step and the current measurement are needed to compute the estimate for the current state.
[src:object-tracking-cv/kalman-filter-p01] In contrast to batch estimation techniques, no history of observations and/or estimates is required.
[src:object-tracking-cv/kalman-filter-p01] In what follows, the notation ${\hat {\mathbf {x} }}_{n\mid m}$ represents the estimate of $\mathbf {x}$ at time *n* given observations up to and including at time *m* ≤ *n*.
[src:object-tracking-cv/kalman-filter-p01] The algorithm structure of the Kalman filter resembles that of Alpha beta filter.
[src:object-tracking-cv/kalman-filter-p01] The Kalman filter can be written as a single equation; however, it is most often conceptualized as two distinct phases: "Predict" and "Update".
[src:object-tracking-cv/kalman-filter-p01] The predict phase uses the state estimate from the previous timestep to produce an estimate of the state at the current timestep.
[src:object-tracking-cv/kalman-filter-p01] This predicted state estimate is also known as the *a priori* state estimate because, although it is an estimate of the state at the current timestep, it does not include observation information from the current timestep.
[src:object-tracking-cv/kalman-filter-p01] In the update phase, the innovation (the pre-fit residual), i.e. the difference between the current *a priori* prediction and the current observation information, is multiplied by the optimal Kalman gain and combined with the previous state estimate to refine the state estimate.
[src:object-tracking-cv/kalman-filter-p01] This improved estimate based on the current observation is termed the *a posteriori* state estimate.
[src:object-tracking-cv/kalman-filter-p01] Typically, the two phases alternate, with the prediction advancing the state until the next scheduled observation, and the update incorporating the observation.
[src:object-tracking-cv/kalman-filter-p01] However, this is not necessary; if an observation is unavailable for some reason, the update may be skipped and multiple prediction procedures performed.
[src:object-tracking-cv/kalman-filter-p01] Likewise, if multiple independent observations are available at the same time, multiple update procedures may be performed (typically with different observation matrices **H***k*).
[src:object-tracking-cv/kalman-filter-p01] The second formula for the updated (*a posteriori*) estimate covariance above is known as the "Joseph form" that is often used in applications (numerically more stable than the more simple usual formulation).
[src:object-tracking-cv/kalman-filter-p01] Proof of the formulae is found in the *derivations* section, where the formula valid for any **K**k is also shown.
[src:object-tracking-cv/kalman-filter-p01] This expression reminds us of a linear interpolation, $x=(1-t)(a)+t(b)$ for t between [0,1].
[src:object-tracking-cv/kalman-filter-p01] This expression also resembles the alpha beta filter update step.
[src:object-tracking-cv/kalman-filter-p01] where $\operatorname {E} [\xi ]$ is the expected value of $\xi$ .
[src:object-tracking-cv/kalman-filter-p01] That is, all estimates have a mean error of zero.
[src:object-tracking-cv/kalman-filter-p01] so covariance matrices accurately reflect the covariance of estimates.
[src:object-tracking-cv/kalman-filter-p01] Practical implementation of a Kalman Filter is often difficult due to the difficulty of getting a good estimate of the noise covariance matrices **Q***k* and **R***k*.
[src:object-tracking-cv/kalman-filter-p01] Extensive research has been done to estimate these covariances from data.
[src:object-tracking-cv/kalman-filter-p01] One practical method of doing this is the *autocovariance least-squares* (ALS) technique that uses the time-lagged autocovariances of routine operating data to estimate the covariances.
[src:object-tracking-cv/kalman-filter-p01] The GNU Octave and Matlab code used to calculate the noise covariance matrices using the ALS technique is available online using the GNU General Public License.
[src:object-tracking-cv/kalman-filter-p01] Another approach is the *Optimized Kalman Filter* (OKF), which considers the covariance matrices not as representatives of the noise, but rather, as parameters aimed to achieve the most accurate state estimation.
[src:object-tracking-cv/kalman-filter-p01] These two views coincide under the KF assumptions, but often contradict each other in real systems.
[src:object-tracking-cv/kalman-filter-p01] Thus, OKF's state estimation is more robust to modeling inaccuracies.
[src:object-tracking-cv/kalman-filter-p01] The Kalman filter provides an optimal state estimation in cases where a) the model matches the real system perfectly, b) the entering noise is "white" (uncorrelated), and c) the covariances of the noise are known exactly.
[src:object-tracking-cv/kalman-filter-p01] Correlated noise can also be treated using Kalman filters.
[src:object-tracking-cv/kalman-filter-p01] Several methods for the noise covariance estimation have been proposed during past decades, including ALS, mentioned in the section above.
[src:object-tracking-cv/kalman-filter-p01] More generally, if the model assumptions do not match the real system perfectly, then optimal state estimation is not necessarily obtained by setting **Q***k* and **R***k* to the covariances of the noise.
[src:object-tracking-cv/kalman-filter-p01] Instead, in that case, the parameters **Q***k* and **R***k* may be set to explicitly optimize the state estimation, e.g., using standard supervised learning.
[src:object-tracking-cv/kalman-filter-p01] After the covariances are set, it is useful to evaluate the performance of the filter; i.e., whether it is possible to improve the state estimation quality.
[src:object-tracking-cv/kalman-filter-p01] If the Kalman filter works optimally, the innovation sequence (the output prediction error) is a white noise, therefore the whiteness property of the innovations measures filter performance.
[src:object-tracking-cv/kalman-filter-p01] Several different methods can be used for this purpose.
[src:object-tracking-cv/kalman-filter-p01] If the noise terms are distributed in a non-Gaussian manner, methods for assessing performance of the filter estimate, which use probability inequalities or large-sample theory, are known in the literature.
[src:object-tracking-cv/kalman-filter-p01] Consider a truck on frictionless, straight rails.
[src:object-tracking-cv/kalman-filter-p01] Initially, the truck is stationary at position 0, but it is buffeted this way and that by random uncontrolled forces.
[src:object-tracking-cv/kalman-filter-p01] We measure the position of the truck every Δ*t* seconds, but these measurements are imprecise; we want to maintain a model of the truck's position and velocity.
[src:object-tracking-cv/kalman-filter-p01] We show here how we derive the model from which we create our Kalman filter.
[src:object-tracking-cv/kalman-filter-p01] Since $\mathbf {F} ,\mathbf {H} ,\mathbf {R} ,\mathbf {Q}$ are constant, their time indices are dropped.
[src:object-tracking-cv/kalman-filter-p01] where ${\dot {x}}$ is the velocity, that is, the derivative of position with respect to time.
[src:object-tracking-cv/kalman-filter-p01] We assume that between the (*k* − 1) and *k* timestep, uncontrolled forces cause a constant acceleration of *a**k* that is normally distributed with mean 0 and standard deviation *σ**a*.
[src:object-tracking-cv/kalman-filter-p01] (there is no $\mathbf {B} u$ term since there are no known control inputs.
[src:object-tracking-cv/kalman-filter-p01] The matrix $\mathbf {Q}$ is not full rank (it is of rank one if $\Delta t\neq 0$ ).
[src:object-tracking-cv/kalman-filter-p01] Hence, the distribution $N(0,\mathbf {Q} )$ is not absolutely continuous and has no probability density function.
[src:object-tracking-cv/kalman-filter-p01] At each time phase, a noisy measurement of the true position of the truck is made.
[src:object-tracking-cv/kalman-filter-p01] Let us suppose the measurement noise *v**k* is also distributed normally, with mean 0 and standard deviation *σ**z*.
[src:object-tracking-cv/kalman-filter-p01] The filter will then prefer the information from the first measurements over the information already in the model.
[src:object-tracking-cv/kalman-filter-p01] For simplicity, assume that the control input $\mathbf {u} _{k}=\mathbf {0}$ .
[src:object-tracking-cv/kalman-filter-p01] A similar equation holds if we include a non-zero control input.
[src:object-tracking-cv/kalman-filter-p01] Gain matrices $\mathbf {K} _{k}$ and covariance matrices $\mathbf {P} _{k\mid k}$ evolve independently of the measurements $\mathbf {z} _{k}$ .
[src:object-tracking-cv/kalman-filter-p01] Since these depend only on the model, and not the measurements, they may be computed offline.
[src:object-tracking-cv/kalman-filter-p01] Convergence of the gain matrices $\mathbf {K} _{k}$ to an asymptotic matrix $\mathbf {K} _{\infty }$ applies for conditions established in Walrand and Dimakis.
[src:object-tracking-cv/kalman-filter-p01] If the $\mathbf {P} _{k\mid k}$ series converges, then it converges exponentially to an asymptotic $\mathbf {P} _{\infty }$ , assuming non-zero plant noise.
[src:object-tracking-cv/kalman-filter-p01] Recent analysis has shown that the *rate and nature* of this convergence can involve multiple coequal modes, including oscillatory components, depending on the eigenstructure of the Jacobian of the above Riccati map evaluated at $\mathbf {P} _{\infty }$ .
[src:object-tracking-cv/kalman-filter-p01] For the moving truck example described above, with $\Delta t=1$ and $\sigma _{a}^{2}=\sigma _{z}^{2}=\sigma _{x}^{2}=\sigma _{\dot {x}}^{2}=1$ , simulation shows convergence in $10$ iterations.
[src:object-tracking-cv/kalman-filter-p01] The asymptotic gain is then computed as before.
[src:object-tracking-cv/kalman-filter-p01] The Kalman filter can be derived as a generalized least squares method operating on previous data.
[src:object-tracking-cv/kalman-filter-p01] This formula (sometimes known as the **Joseph form** of the covariance update equation) is valid for any value of **K***k*.
[src:object-tracking-cv/kalman-filter-p01] It turns out that if **K***k* is the optimal Kalman gain, this can be simplified further as shown below.
[src:object-tracking-cv/kalman-filter-p01] The Kalman filter is a minimum mean-square error (MMSE) estimator.
[src:object-tracking-cv/kalman-filter-p01] We seek to minimize the expected value of the square of the magnitude of this vector, $\operatorname {E} \left[\left\|\mathbf {x} _{k}-{\hat {\mathbf {x} }}_{k|k}\right\|^{2}\right]$ .
[src:object-tracking-cv/kalman-filter-p01] This is equivalent to minimizing the trace of the *a posteriori* estimate covariance matrix $\mathbf {P} _{k|k}$ .
[src:object-tracking-cv/kalman-filter-p01] The trace is minimized when its matrix derivative with respect to the gain matrix is zero.
[src:object-tracking-cv/kalman-filter-p01] This gain, which is known as the *optimal Kalman gain*, is the one that yields MMSE estimates when used.
[src:object-tracking-cv/kalman-filter-p01] The formula used to calculate the *a posteriori* error covariance can be simplified when the Kalman gain equals the optimal value derived above.
[src:object-tracking-cv/kalman-filter-p01] This formula is computationally cheaper and thus nearly always used in practice, but is only correct for the optimal gain.
[src:object-tracking-cv/kalman-filter-p01] If arithmetic precision is unusually low causing problems with numerical stability, or if a non-optimal Kalman gain is deliberately used, this simplification cannot be applied; the *a posteriori* error covariance formula as derived above (Joseph form) must be used.
[src:object-tracking-cv/kalman-filter-p01] The Kalman filtering equations provide an estimate of the state ${\hat {\mathbf {x} }}_{k\mid k}$ and its error covariance $\mathbf {P} _{k\mid k}$ recursively.
[src:object-tracking-cv/kalman-filter-p01] The estimate and its quality depend on the system parameters and the noise statistics fed as inputs to the estimator.
[src:object-tracking-cv/kalman-filter-p01] This section analyzes the effect of uncertainties in the statistical inputs to the filter.
[src:object-tracking-cv/kalman-filter-p01] no longer provides the actual error covariance.
[src:object-tracking-cv/kalman-filter-p01] In most real-time applications, the covariance matrices that are used in designing the Kalman filter are different from the actual (true) noise covariances matrices.
[src:object-tracking-cv/kalman-filter-p01] This sensitivity analysis describes the behavior of the estimation error covariance when the noise covariances as well as the system matrices $\mathbf {F} _{k}$ and $\mathbf {H} _{k}$ that are fed as inputs to the filter are incorrect.
[src:object-tracking-cv/kalman-filter-p01] Thus, the sensitivity analysis describes the robustness (or sensitivity) of the estimator to misspecified statistical and parametric inputs to the estimator.
[src:object-tracking-cv/kalman-filter-p01] This discussion is limited to the error sensitivity analysis for the case of statistical uncertainties.
[src:object-tracking-cv/kalman-filter-p01] Here the actual noise covariances are denoted by $\mathbf {Q} _{k}^{a}$ and $\mathbf {R} _{k}^{a}$ respectively, whereas the design values used in the estimator are $\mathbf {Q} _{k}$ and $\mathbf {R} _{k}$ respectively.
[src:object-tracking-cv/kalman-filter-p01] The actual error covariance is denoted by $\mathbf {P} _{k\mid k}^{a}$ and $\mathbf {P} _{k\mid k}$ as computed by the Kalman filter is referred to as the Riccati variable.
[src:object-tracking-cv/kalman-filter-p01] The recursive expressions for $\mathbf {P} _{k\mid k}^{a}$ and $\mathbf {P} _{k\mid k}$ are identical except for the presence of $\mathbf {Q} _{k}^{a}$ and $\mathbf {R} _{k}^{a}$ in place of the design values $\mathbf {Q} _{k}$ and $\mathbf {R} _{k}$ respectively.
[src:object-tracking-cv/kalman-filter-p01] Researches have been done to analyze Kalman filter system's robustness.
[src:object-tracking-cv/kalman-filter-p01] One problem with the Kalman filter is its numerical stability.
[src:object-tracking-cv/kalman-filter-p01] If the process noise covariance **Q***k* is small, round-off error often causes a small positive eigenvalue of the state covariance matrix **P** to be computed as a negative number.
[src:object-tracking-cv/kalman-filter-p01] This renders the numerical representation of **P** indefinite, while its true form is positive-definite.
[src:object-tracking-cv/kalman-filter-p01] Positive definite matrices have the property that they have a factorization into the product of a non-singular, lower-triangular matrix **S** and its transpose : **P** = **S**·**S**T .
[src:object-tracking-cv/kalman-filter-p01] The factor **S** can be computed efficiently using the Cholesky factorization algorithm.
[src:object-tracking-cv/kalman-filter-p01] This product form of the covariance matrix **P** is guaranteed to be symmetric, and for all 1 <= k <= n, the k-th diagonal element **P**kk is equal to the square of the euclidean norm of the k-th row of **S**, which is necessarily positive.
[src:object-tracking-cv/kalman-filter-p01] Between the two, the U-D factorization uses the same amount of storage, and somewhat less computation, and is the most commonly used triangular factorization.
[src:object-tracking-cv/kalman-filter-p01] Efficient algorithms for the Kalman prediction and update steps in the factored form were developed by G.
[src:object-tracking-cv/kalman-filter-p01] The **L**·**D**·**L**T decomposition of the innovation covariance matrix **S**k is the basis for another type of numerically efficient and robust square root filter.
[src:object-tracking-cv/kalman-filter-p01] The algorithm starts with the LU decomposition as implemented in the Linear Algebra PACKage (LAPACK).
[src:object-tracking-cv/kalman-filter-p01] These results are further factored into the **L**·**D**·**L**T structure with methods given by Golub and Van Loan (algorithm 4.1.2) for a symmetric nonsingular matrix.
[src:object-tracking-cv/kalman-filter-p01] Any singular covariance matrix is pivoted so that the first diagonal partition is nonsingular and well-conditioned.
[src:object-tracking-cv/kalman-filter-p01] The pivoting algorithm must retain any portion of the innovation covariance matrix directly corresponding to observed state-variables **H**k·**x**k|k-1 that are associated with auxiliary observations in **y**k.
[src:object-tracking-cv/kalman-filter-p01] The **l**·**d**·**l**t square-root filter requires orthogonalization of the observation vector.
[src:object-tracking-cv/kalman-filter-p01] This may be done with the inverse square-root of the covariance matrix for the auxiliary variables using Method 2 in Higham (2002, p.
[src:object-tracking-cv/kalman-filter-p01] The Kalman filter is efficient for sequential data processing on central processing units (CPUs), but in its original form it is inefficient on parallel architectures such as graphics processing units (GPUs).
[src:object-tracking-cv/kalman-filter-p01] It is however possible to express the filter-update routine in terms of an associative operator using the formulation in Särkkä and García-Fernández (2021).
[src:object-tracking-cv/kalman-filter-p01] The filter solution can then be retrieved by the use of a prefix sum algorithm which can be efficiently implemented on GPU.
[src:object-tracking-cv/kalman-filter-p01] This reduces the computational complexity from $O(N)$ in the number of time steps to $O(\log(N))$ .
[src:object-tracking-cv/kalman-filter-p02] The Kalman filter can be presented as one of the simplest dynamic Bayesian networks.
[src:object-tracking-cv/kalman-filter-p02] The Kalman filter calculates estimates of the true values of states recursively over time using incoming measurements and a mathematical process model.
[src:object-tracking-cv/kalman-filter-p02] Similarly, recursive Bayesian estimation calculates estimates of an unknown probability density function (PDF) recursively over time using incoming measurements and a mathematical process model.
[src:object-tracking-cv/kalman-filter-p02] In recursive Bayesian estimation, the true state is assumed to be an unobserved Markov process, and the measurements are the observed states of a hidden Markov model (HMM).
[src:object-tracking-cv/kalman-filter-p02] Because of the Markov assumption, the true state is conditionally independent of all earlier states given the immediately previous state.
[src:object-tracking-cv/kalman-filter-p02] Similarly, the measurement at the *k*-th timestep is dependent only upon the current state and is conditionally independent of all other states given the current state.
[src:object-tracking-cv/kalman-filter-p02] However, when a Kalman filter is used to estimate the state **x**, the probability distribution of interest is that associated with the current states conditioned on the measurements up to the current timestep.
[src:object-tracking-cv/kalman-filter-p02] This is achieved by marginalizing out the previous states and dividing by the probability of the measurement set.
[src:object-tracking-cv/kalman-filter-p02] This results in the *predict* and *update* phases of the Kalman filter written probabilistically.
[src:object-tracking-cv/kalman-filter-p02] The probability distribution of the update is proportional to the product of the measurement likelihood and the predicted state.
[src:object-tracking-cv/kalman-filter-p02] The PDF at the previous timestep is assumed inductively to be the estimated state and covariance.
[src:object-tracking-cv/kalman-filter-p02] This is justified because, as an optimal estimator, the Kalman filter makes best use of the measurements, therefore the PDF for $\mathbf {x} _{k}$ given the measurements $\mathbf {Z} _{k}$ is the Kalman filter estimate.
[src:object-tracking-cv/kalman-filter-p02] Related to the recursive Bayesian interpretation described above, the Kalman filter can be viewed as a generative model, i.e., a process for *generating* a stream of random observations **z** = (**z**0, **z**1, **z**2, ...).
[src:object-tracking-cv/kalman-filter-p02] This process has identical structure to the hidden Markov model, except that the discrete state and observations are replaced with continuous variables sampled from Gaussian distributions.
[src:object-tracking-cv/kalman-filter-p02] In some applications, it is useful to compute the *probability* that a Kalman filter with a given set of parameters (prior distribution, transition and observation models, and control inputs) would generate a particular observed signal.
[src:object-tracking-cv/kalman-filter-p02] This probability is known as the marginal likelihood because it integrates over ("marginalizes out") the values of the hidden state variables, so it can be computed using only the observed signal.
[src:object-tracking-cv/kalman-filter-p02] The marginal likelihood can be useful to evaluate different parameter choices, or to compare the Kalman filter against other models using Bayesian model comparison.
[src:object-tracking-cv/kalman-filter-p02] It is straightforward to compute the marginal likelihood as a side effect of the recursive filtering computation.
[src:object-tracking-cv/kalman-filter-p02] i.e., a product of Gaussian densities, each corresponding to the density of one observation **z***k* under the current filtering distribution $\mathbf {H} _{k}{\hat {\mathbf {x} }}_{k\mid k-1},\mathbf {S} _{k}$ .
[src:object-tracking-cv/kalman-filter-p02] This can easily be computed as a simple recursive update; however, to avoid numeric underflow, in a practical implementation it is usually desirable to compute the *log* marginal likelihood $\ell =\log p(\mathbf {z} )$ instead.
[src:object-tracking-cv/kalman-filter-p02] where $d_{y}$ is the dimension of the measurement vector.
[src:object-tracking-cv/kalman-filter-p02] An important application where such a (log) likelihood of the observations (given the filter parameters) is used is multi-target tracking.
[src:object-tracking-cv/kalman-filter-p02] For example, consider an object tracking scenario where a stream of observations is the input, however, it is unknown how many objects are in the scene (or, the number of objects is known but is greater than one).
[src:object-tracking-cv/kalman-filter-p02] For such a scenario, it can be unknown apriori which observations/measurements were generated by which object.
[src:object-tracking-cv/kalman-filter-p02] A multiple hypothesis tracker (MHT) typically will form different track association hypotheses, where each hypothesis can be considered as a Kalman filter (for the linear Gaussian case) with a specific set of parameters associated with the hypothesized object.
[src:object-tracking-cv/kalman-filter-p02] Thus, it is important to compute the likelihood of the observations for the different hypotheses under consideration, such that the most-likely one can be found.
[src:object-tracking-cv/kalman-filter-p02] Additionally, the information filter allows for system information initialization according to ${I_{1|0}=P_{1|0}^{-1}=0}$ , which would not be possible for the regular Kalman filter.
[src:object-tracking-cv/kalman-filter-p02] In the information filter, or inverse covariance filter, the estimated covariance and estimated state are replaced by the information matrix and information vector respectively.
[src:object-tracking-cv/kalman-filter-p02] The information update now becomes a trivial sum.
[src:object-tracking-cv/kalman-filter-p02] The main advantage of the information filter is that *N* measurements can be filtered at each time step simply by summing their information matrices and vectors.
[src:object-tracking-cv/kalman-filter-p02] To predict the information filter the information matrix and vector can be converted back to their state space equivalents, or alternatively the information space prediction can be used.
[src:object-tracking-cv/kalman-filter-p02] The optimal fixed-lag smoother provides the optimal estimate of ${\hat {\mathbf {x} }}_{k-N\mid k}$ for a given fixed-lag N using the measurements from $\mathbf {z} _{1}$ to $\mathbf {z} _{k}$ .
[src:object-tracking-cv/kalman-filter-p02] The optimal fixed-interval smoother provides the optimal estimate of ${\hat {\mathbf {x} }}_{k\mid n}$ ( $k<n$ ) using the measurements from a fixed interval $\mathbf {z} _{1}$ to $\mathbf {z} _{n}$ .
[src:object-tracking-cv/kalman-filter-p02] There are several smoothing algorithms in common use.
[src:object-tracking-cv/kalman-filter-p02] The Rauch–Tung–Striebel (RTS) smoother is an efficient two-pass algorithm for fixed interval smoothing.
[src:object-tracking-cv/kalman-filter-p02] The forward pass is the same as the regular Kalman filter algorithm.
[src:object-tracking-cv/kalman-filter-p02] These *filtered* a-priori and a-posteriori state estimates ${\hat {\mathbf {x} }}_{k\mid k-1}$ , ${\hat {\mathbf {x} }}_{k\mid k}$ and covariances $\mathbf {P} _{k\mid k-1}$ , $\mathbf {P} _{k\mid k}$ are saved for use in the backward pass (for retrodiction).
[src:object-tracking-cv/kalman-filter-p02] In the backward pass, we compute the *smoothed* state estimates ${\hat {\mathbf {x} }}_{k\mid n}$ and covariances $\mathbf {P} _{k\mid n}$ .
[src:object-tracking-cv/kalman-filter-p02] $\mathbf {x} _{k\mid k}$ is the a-posteriori state estimate of timestep k and $\mathbf {x} _{k+1\mid k}$ is the a-priori state estimate of timestep $k+1$ .
[src:object-tracking-cv/kalman-filter-p02] The same notation applies to the covariance.
[src:object-tracking-cv/kalman-filter-p02] An alternative to the RTS algorithm is the modified Bryson–Frazier (MBF) fixed interval smoother developed by Bierman.
[src:object-tracking-cv/kalman-filter-p02] This also uses a backward pass that processes data saved from the Kalman filter forward pass.
[src:object-tracking-cv/kalman-filter-p02] The equations for the backward pass involve the recursive computation of data which are used at each observation time to compute the smoothed state and covariance.
[src:object-tracking-cv/kalman-filter-p02] An important advantage of the MBF is that it does not require finding the inverse of the covariance matrix.
[src:object-tracking-cv/kalman-filter-p02] Bierman's derivation is based on the RTS smoother, which assumes that the underlying distributions are Gaussian.
[src:object-tracking-cv/kalman-filter-p02] However, a derivation of the MBF based on the concept of the fixed point smoother, which does not require the Gaussian assumption, is given by Gibbs.
[src:object-tracking-cv/kalman-filter-p02] The MBF can also be used to perform consistency checks on the filter residuals and the difference between the value of a filter state after an update and the smoothed value of the state, that is $\mathbf {x} _{k\mid k}-\mathbf {x} _{k\mid n}$ .
[src:object-tracking-cv/kalman-filter-p02] The minimum-variance smoother can attain the best-possible error performance, provided that the models are linear, their parameters and the noise statistics are known precisely.
[src:object-tracking-cv/kalman-filter-p02] This smoother is a time-varying state-space generalization of the optimal non-causal Wiener filter.
[src:object-tracking-cv/kalman-filter-p02] The smoother calculations are done in two passes.
[src:object-tracking-cv/kalman-filter-p02] The above system is known as the inverse Wiener-Hopf factor.
[src:object-tracking-cv/kalman-filter-p02] The backward recursion is the adjoint of the above forward system.
[src:object-tracking-cv/kalman-filter-p02] The result of the backward pass $\beta _{k}$ may be calculated by operating the forward equations on the time-reversed $\alpha _{k}$ and time reversing the result.
[src:object-tracking-cv/kalman-filter-p02] which is identical to the minimum-variance Kalman filter.
[src:object-tracking-cv/kalman-filter-p02] The above solutions minimize the variance of the output estimation error.
[src:object-tracking-cv/kalman-filter-p02] Note that the Rauch–Tung–Striebel smoother derivation assumes that the underlying distributions are Gaussian, whereas the minimum-variance solutions do not.
[src:object-tracking-cv/kalman-filter-p02] Optimal smoothers for state estimation and input estimation can be constructed similarly.
[src:object-tracking-cv/kalman-filter-p02] A continuous-time version of the above smoother is described in.
[src:object-tracking-cv/kalman-filter-p02] Expectation–maximization algorithms may be employed to calculate approximate maximum likelihood estimates of unknown state-space parameters within minimum-variance filters and smoothers.
[src:object-tracking-cv/kalman-filter-p02] Often uncertainties remain within problem assumptions.
[src:object-tracking-cv/kalman-filter-p02] A smoother that accommodates uncertainties can be designed by adding a positive definite term to the Riccati equation.
[src:object-tracking-cv/kalman-filter-p02] In cases where the models are nonlinear, step-wise linearizations may be within the minimum-variance filter and smoother recursions (extended Kalman filtering).
[src:object-tracking-cv/kalman-filter-p02] Pioneering research on the perception of sounds at different frequencies was conducted by Fletcher and Munson in the 1930s.
[src:object-tracking-cv/kalman-filter-p02] Their work led to a standard way of weighting measured sound levels within investigations of industrial noise and hearing loss.
[src:object-tracking-cv/kalman-filter-p02] Frequency weightings have since been used within filter and controller designs to manage performance within bands of interest.
[src:object-tracking-cv/kalman-filter-p02] Typically, a frequency shaping function is used to weight the average power of the error spectral density in a specified frequency band.
[src:object-tracking-cv/kalman-filter-p02] Let $\mathbf {y} -{\hat {\mathbf {y} }}$ denote the output estimation error exhibited by a conventional Kalman filter.
[src:object-tracking-cv/kalman-filter-p02] Also, let $\mathbf {W}$ denote a causal frequency weighting transfer function.
[src:object-tracking-cv/kalman-filter-p02] The optimum solution which minimizes the variance of $\mathbf {W} \left(\mathbf {y} -{\hat {\mathbf {y} }}\right)$ arises by simply constructing $\mathbf {W} ^{-1}{\hat {\mathbf {y} }}$ .
[src:object-tracking-cv/kalman-filter-p02] The design of $\mathbf {W}$ remains an open question.
[src:object-tracking-cv/kalman-filter-p02] One way of proceeding is to identify a system which generates the estimation error and setting $\mathbf {W}$ equal to the inverse of that system.
[src:object-tracking-cv/kalman-filter-p02] This procedure may be iterated to obtain mean-square error improvement at the cost of increased filter order.
[src:object-tracking-cv/kalman-filter-p02] The same technique can be applied to smoothers.
[src:object-tracking-cv/kalman-filter-p02] The basic Kalman filter is limited to a linear assumption.
[src:object-tracking-cv/kalman-filter-p02] More complex systems, however, can be nonlinear.
[src:object-tracking-cv/kalman-filter-p02] The nonlinearity can be associated either with the process model or with the observation model or with both.
[src:object-tracking-cv/kalman-filter-p02] The most common variants of Kalman filters for non-linear systems are the Extended Kalman Filter and Unscented Kalman filter.
[src:object-tracking-cv/kalman-filter-p02] The suitability of which filter to use depends on the non-linearity indices of the process and observation model.
[src:object-tracking-cv/kalman-filter-p02] In the extended Kalman filter (EKF), the state transition and observation models need not be linear functions of the state but may instead be nonlinear functions.
[src:object-tracking-cv/kalman-filter-p02] These functions are of differentiable type.
[src:object-tracking-cv/kalman-filter-p02] The function *f* can be used to compute the predicted state from the previous estimate and similarly the function *h* can be used to compute the predicted measurement from the predicted state.
[src:object-tracking-cv/kalman-filter-p02] However, *f* and *h* cannot be applied to the covariance directly.
[src:object-tracking-cv/kalman-filter-p02] Instead a matrix of partial derivatives (the Jacobian) is computed.
[src:object-tracking-cv/kalman-filter-p02] At each timestep the Jacobian is evaluated with current predicted states.
[src:object-tracking-cv/kalman-filter-p02] These matrices can be used in the Kalman filter equations.
[src:object-tracking-cv/kalman-filter-p02] This process essentially linearizes the nonlinear function around the current estimate.
[src:object-tracking-cv/kalman-filter-p02] When the state transition and observation models—that is, the predict and update functions f and h —are highly nonlinear, the extended Kalman filter can give particularly poor performance.
[src:object-tracking-cv/kalman-filter-p02] This is because the covariance is propagated through linearization of the underlying nonlinear model.
[src:object-tracking-cv/kalman-filter-p02] The unscented Kalman filter (UKF) uses a deterministic sampling technique known as the unscented transformation (UT) to pick a minimal set of sample points (called sigma points) around the mean.
[src:object-tracking-cv/kalman-filter-p02] The sigma points are then propagated through the nonlinear functions, from which a new mean and covariance estimate are formed.
[src:object-tracking-cv/kalman-filter-p02] The resulting filter depends on how the transformed statistics of the UT are calculated and which set of sigma points are used.
[src:object-tracking-cv/kalman-filter-p02] It should be remarked that it is always possible to construct new UKFs in a consistent way.
[src:object-tracking-cv/kalman-filter-p02] For certain systems, the resulting UKF more accurately estimates the true mean and covariance.
[src:object-tracking-cv/kalman-filter-p02] This can be verified with Monte Carlo sampling or Taylor series expansion of the posterior statistics.
[src:object-tracking-cv/kalman-filter-p02] Typically, $\mathbf {A}$ is obtained via Cholesky decomposition of $\mathbf {P} _{k-1\mid k-1}$ .
[src:object-tracking-cv/kalman-filter-p02] With some care the filter equations can be expressed in such a way that $\mathbf {A}$ is evaluated directly without intermediate calculations of $\mathbf {P} _{k-1\mid k-1}$ .
[src:object-tracking-cv/kalman-filter-p02] This is referred to as the *square-root unscented Kalman filter*.
[src:object-tracking-cv/kalman-filter-p02] The weight of the mean value, $W_{0}$ , can be chosen arbitrarily.
[src:object-tracking-cv/kalman-filter-p02] $\alpha$ and $\kappa$ control the spread of the sigma points. $\beta$ is related to the distribution of x .
[src:object-tracking-cv/kalman-filter-p02] Note that this is an overparameterization in the sense that any one of $\alpha$ , $\beta$ and $\kappa$ can be chosen arbitrarily.
[src:object-tracking-cv/kalman-filter-p02] Appropriate values depend on the problem at hand, but a typical recommendation is $\alpha =1$ , $\beta =0$ , and $\kappa \approx 3L/2$ .
[src:object-tracking-cv/kalman-filter-p02] If the true distribution of x is Gaussian, $\beta =2$ is optimal.
[src:object-tracking-cv/kalman-filter-p02] As with the EKF, the UKF prediction can be used independently from the UKF update, in combination with a linear (or indeed EKF) update, or vice versa.
[src:object-tracking-cv/kalman-filter-p02] Given estimates of the mean and covariance, ${\hat {\mathbf {x} }}_{k-1\mid k-1}$ and $\mathbf {P} _{k-1\mid k-1}$ , one obtains $N=2L+1$ sigma points as described in the section above.
[src:object-tracking-cv/kalman-filter-p02] The sigma points are propagated through the transition function *f*.
[src:object-tracking-cv/kalman-filter-p02] The propagated sigma points are weighed to produce the predicted mean and covariance.
[src:object-tracking-cv/kalman-filter-p02] where $W_{j}^{a}$ are the first-order weights of the original sigma points, and $W_{j}^{c}$ are the second-order weights.
[src:object-tracking-cv/kalman-filter-p02] The matrix $\mathbf {Q} _{k}$ is the covariance of the transition noise, $\mathbf {w} _{k}$ .
[src:object-tracking-cv/kalman-filter-p02] These sigma points are transformed through the measurement function h .
[src:object-tracking-cv/kalman-filter-p02] Then the empirical mean and covariance of the transformed points are calculated.
[src:object-tracking-cv/kalman-filter-p02] where $\mathbf {R} _{k}$ is the covariance matrix of the observation noise, $\mathbf {v} _{k}$ .
[src:object-tracking-cv/kalman-filter-p02] This replaces the generative specification of the standard Kalman filter with a discriminative model for the latent states given observations.
[src:object-tracking-cv/kalman-filter-p02] Such an approach proves particularly useful when the dimensionality of the observations is much greater than that of the latent states and can be used to build filters that are particularly robust to nonstationarities in the observation model.
[src:object-tracking-cv/kalman-filter-p02] Adaptive Kalman filters allow to adapt for process dynamics which are not modeled in the process model $\mathbf {F} (t)$ , which happens for example in the context of a maneuvering target when a constant velocity (reduced order) Kalman filter is employed for tracking.
[src:object-tracking-cv/kalman-filter-p02] Kalman–Bucy filtering (named for Richard Snowden Bucy) is a continuous time version of Kalman filtering.
[src:object-tracking-cv/kalman-filter-p02] where $\mathbf {Q} (t)$ and $\mathbf {R} (t)$ represent the intensities of the two white noise terms $\mathbf {w} (t)$ and $\mathbf {v} (t)$ , respectively.
[src:object-tracking-cv/kalman-filter-p02] The distinction between the prediction and update steps of discrete-time Kalman filtering does not exist in continuous time.
[src:object-tracking-cv/kalman-filter-p02] The second differential equation, for the covariance, is an example of a Riccati equation.
[src:object-tracking-cv/kalman-filter-p02] Nonlinear generalizations to Kalman–Bucy filters include continuous time extended Kalman filter.
[src:object-tracking-cv/kalman-filter-p02] Most physical systems are represented as continuous-time models while discrete-time measurements are made frequently for state estimation via a digital processor.
[src:object-tracking-cv/kalman-filter-p02] The prediction equations are derived from those of continuous-time Kalman filter without update from measurements, i.e., $\mathbf {K} (t)=0$ .
[src:object-tracking-cv/kalman-filter-p02] The predicted state and covariance are calculated respectively by solving a set of differential equations with the initial value equal to the estimate at the previous step.
[src:object-tracking-cv/kalman-filter-p02] For the case of linear time invariant systems, the continuous time dynamics can be exactly discretized into a discrete time system using matrix exponentials.
[src:object-tracking-cv/kalman-filter-p02] The update equations are identical to those of the discrete-time Kalman filter.
[src:object-tracking-cv/kalman-filter-p02] The traditional Kalman filter has also been employed for the recovery of sparse, possibly dynamic, signals from noisy observations.
[src:object-tracking-cv/kalman-filter-p02] Recent works utilize notions from the theory of compressed sensing/sampling, such as the restricted isometry property and related probabilistic recovery arguments, for sequentially estimating the sparse state in intrinsically low-dimensional systems.
[src:object-tracking-cv/kalman-filter-p02] Since linear Gaussian state-space models lead to Gaussian processes, Kalman filters can be viewed as sequential solvers for Gaussian process regression.
[src:object-tracking-cv/motion-capture] In films, television shows and video games, motion capture refers to recording actions of human actors and using that information to animate digital character models in 2D or 3D computer animation.
[src:object-tracking-cv/motion-capture] When it includes face and fingers or captures subtle expressions or voices, it is often referred to as **performance capture**.
[src:object-tracking-cv/motion-capture] In many fields, motion capture is sometimes called **motion tracking**, but in filmmaking and games, motion tracking usually refers more to match moving.
[src:object-tracking-cv/motion-capture] In motion capture sessions, movements of one or more actors are sampled many times per second.
[src:object-tracking-cv/motion-capture] Whereas early techniques used images from multiple cameras to calculate 3D positions, often the purpose of motion capture is to record only the movements of the actor, not their visual appearance.
[src:object-tracking-cv/motion-capture] This *animation data* is mapped to a 3D model so that the model performs the same actions as the actor.
[src:object-tracking-cv/motion-capture] This process may be contrasted with the older technique of rotoscoping.
[src:object-tracking-cv/motion-capture] Camera movements can also be motion captured so that a virtual camera in the scene will pan, tilt or dolly around the stage driven by a camera operator while the actor is performing.
[src:object-tracking-cv/motion-capture] At the same time, the motion capture system can capture the camera and props as well as the actor's performance.
[src:object-tracking-cv/motion-capture] This allows the computer-generated characters, images and sets to have the same perspective as the video images from the camera.
[src:object-tracking-cv/motion-capture] A computer processes the data and displays the movements of the actor, providing the desired camera positions in terms of objects in the set.
[src:object-tracking-cv/motion-capture] Retroactively obtaining camera movement data from the captured footage is known as *match moving* or *camera tracking*.
[src:object-tracking-cv/motion-capture] The first virtual actor animated by motion-capture was produced in 1993 by Didier Pourcel and his team at Gribouille.
[src:object-tracking-cv/motion-capture] It involved "cloning" the body and face of French comedian Richard Bohringer, and then animating it with still-nascent motion-capture tools.
[src:object-tracking-cv/motion-capture] There are many applications of motion capture.
[src:object-tracking-cv/motion-capture] The most common are for video games, movies, and movement capture, however there is a research application for this technology being used at Purdue University in robotics development.
[src:object-tracking-cv/motion-capture] Video games often use motion capture to animate athletes, martial artists, and other in-game characters.
[src:object-tracking-cv/motion-capture] As early as 1988, an early form of motion capture was used to animate the 2D player characters of Martech's video game *Vixen* (performed by model Corinne Russell) and Magical Company's 2D arcade fighting game *Last Apostle Puppet Show* (to animate digitized sprites).
[src:object-tracking-cv/motion-capture] Motion capture was later notably used to animate the 3D character models in the Sega Model arcade games *Virtua Fighter* (1993) and *Virtua Fighter 2* (1994).
[src:object-tracking-cv/motion-capture] In mid-1995, developer/publisher Acclaim Entertainment had its own in-house motion capture studio built into its headquarters.
[src:object-tracking-cv/motion-capture] Namco's 1995 arcade game *Soul Edge* used passive optical system markers for motion capture.
[src:object-tracking-cv/motion-capture] Motion capture also uses athletes in based-off animated games, such as Naughty Dog's Crash Bandicoot, Insomniac Games' Spyro the Dragon, and Rare's Dinosaur Planet.
[src:object-tracking-cv/motion-capture] Indoor positioning is another application for optical motion capture systems.
[src:object-tracking-cv/motion-capture] Robotics researchers often use motion capture systems when developing and evaluating control, estimation, and perception algorithms and hardware.
[src:object-tracking-cv/motion-capture] In outdoor spaces, it's possible to achieve accuracy to the centimeter by using the Global Navigation Satellite System (GNSS) together with Real-Time Kinematics (RTK).
[src:object-tracking-cv/motion-capture] However, this reduces significantly when there is no line-of-sight to the satellites — such as in indoor environments.
[src:object-tracking-cv/motion-capture] The majority of vendors selling commercial optical motion capture systems provide accessible open source drivers that integrate with the popular Robotic Operating System (ROS) framework, allowing researchers and developers to effectively test their robots during development.
[src:object-tracking-cv/motion-capture] In the field of aerial robotics research, motion capture systems are widely used for positioning as well.
[src:object-tracking-cv/motion-capture] Regulations on airspace usage limit how feasible outdoor experiments can be conducted with Unmanned Aerial Systems (UAS).
[src:object-tracking-cv/motion-capture] Indoor tests can circumvent such restrictions.
[src:object-tracking-cv/motion-capture] Many labs and institutions around the world have built indoor motion capture volumes for this purpose.
[src:object-tracking-cv/motion-capture] Purdue University houses the world's largest indoor motion capture system, inside the Purdue UAS Research and Test (PURT) facility.
[src:object-tracking-cv/motion-capture] PURT is dedicated to UAS research, and provides tracking volume of 600,000 cubic feet using 60 motion capture cameras.
[src:object-tracking-cv/motion-capture] The optical motion capture system is able to track targets in its volume with millimeter accuracy, effectively providing the true position of targets — the "ground truth" baseline in research and development.
[src:object-tracking-cv/motion-capture] Results derived from other sensors and algorithms can then be compared to the ground truth data to evaluate their performance.
[src:object-tracking-cv/motion-capture] Movies use motion capture for CGI effects, in some cases replacing traditional cel animation, and for completely CGI creatures, such as Gollum, The Mummy, King Kong, Davy Jones from *Pirates of the Caribbean*, the Na'vi from the film *Avatar*, and Clu from *Tron: Legacy*.
[src:object-tracking-cv/motion-capture] The Great Goblin, the three Stone-trolls, many of the orcs and goblins in the 2012 film *The Hobbit: An Unexpected Journey*, and Smaug were created using motion capture.
[src:object-tracking-cv/motion-capture] In the 1990 movie *Total Recall*, the sequence where Arnold Schwarzenegger and other actors walk through an X-ray machine was shot using motion capture.
[src:object-tracking-cv/motion-capture] The film *Batman Forever* (1995) used some motion capture for certain visual effects.
[src:object-tracking-cv/motion-capture] Warner Bros. had acquired motion capture technology from arcade video game company Acclaim Entertainment for use in the film's production.
[src:object-tracking-cv/motion-capture] Acclaim's 1995 video game of the same name also used the same motion capture technology to animate the digitized sprite graphics.
[src:object-tracking-cv/motion-capture] The 1999 film *Star Wars: Episode I – The Phantom Menace* was the first feature-length film to include a main character created (Jar Jar Binks, played by Ahmed Best), using motion capture.
[src:object-tracking-cv/motion-capture] The 2000 Indian-American film *Sinbad: Beyond the Veil of Mists* was the first feature-length film made primarily with motion capture, although many character animators also worked on the film, which had a very limited release.
[src:object-tracking-cv/motion-capture] 2001's *Final Fantasy: The Spirits Within* was the first widely released movie to be made with motion capture technology.
[src:object-tracking-cv/motion-capture] Despite its poor box-office intake, supporters of motion capture technology took notice.
[src:object-tracking-cv/motion-capture] Storymind Entertainment, which is an independent Ukrainian studio, created a neo-noir third-person / shooter video game called *My Eyes On You*, using motion capture in order to animate its main character, Jordan Adalien, and along with non-playable characters.
[src:object-tracking-cv/motion-capture] Of the three nominees for the 2006 Academy Award for Best Animated Feature, two of the nominees (*Monster House* and the winner *Happy Feet*) used motion capture, and only Disney**·**Pixar's *Cars* was animated without it.
[src:object-tracking-cv/motion-capture] Since 2001, motion capture has been used extensively to simulate or approximate the look of live-action theater, with nearly photorealistic digital character models.
[src:object-tracking-cv/motion-capture] *The Polar Express* used motion capture to allow Tom Hanks to perform as several distinct digital characters (in which he also provided the voices).
[src:object-tracking-cv/motion-capture] The 2007 adaptation of the saga *Beowulf* animated digital characters whose appearances were based in part on the actors who provided their motions and voices.
[src:object-tracking-cv/motion-capture] James Cameron's highly popular *Avatar* used this technique to create the Na'vi that inhabit Pandora.
[src:object-tracking-cv/motion-capture] The Walt Disney Company has produced Robert Zemeckis's *A Christmas Carol* using this technique.
[src:object-tracking-cv/motion-capture] In 2007, Disney acquired Zemeckis' ImageMovers Digital (that produces motion capture films), but then closed it in 2011, after a box office failure of *Mars Needs Moms*.
[src:object-tracking-cv/motion-capture] Television series produced entirely with motion capture animation include *Laflaque* in Canada, *Sprookjesboom* and *Cafe de Wereld* in The Netherlands, and *Headcases* in the UK.
[src:object-tracking-cv/motion-capture] Virtual reality and augmented reality providers, such as uSens and Gestigon, allow users to interact with digital content in real time by capturing hand motions.
[src:object-tracking-cv/motion-capture] This can be useful for training simulations, visual perception tests, or performing virtual walk-throughs in a 3D environment.
[src:object-tracking-cv/motion-capture] Motion capture technology is frequently used in digital puppetry systems to drive computer-generated characters in real time.
[src:object-tracking-cv/motion-capture] Gait analysis is one application of motion capture in clinical medicine.
[src:object-tracking-cv/motion-capture] Techniques allow clinicians to evaluate human motion across several biomechanical factors, often while streaming this information live into analytical software.
[src:object-tracking-cv/motion-capture] One innovative use is pose detection, which can empower patients during post-surgical recovery or rehabilitation after injuries.
[src:object-tracking-cv/motion-capture] This approach enables continuous monitoring, real-time guidance, and individually tailored programs to enhance patient outcomes.
[src:object-tracking-cv/motion-capture] Some physical therapy clinics utilize motion capture as an objective way to quantify patient progress.
[src:object-tracking-cv/motion-capture] This method allowed views and angles not possible from a pre-rendered animation.
[src:object-tracking-cv/motion-capture] Cameron was so proud of his results that he invited Steven Spielberg and George Lucas on set to view the system in action.
[src:object-tracking-cv/motion-capture] In Marvel's *The Avengers*, Mark Ruffalo used motion capture so he could play his character the Hulk, rather than have him be only CGI as in previous films, making Ruffalo the first actor to play both the human and the Hulk versions of Bruce Banner.
[src:object-tracking-cv/motion-capture] FaceRig software uses facial recognition technology from ULSee.Inc to map a player's facial expressions and the body tracking technology from Perception Neuron to map the body movement onto a 2D or 3D character's motion on-screen.
[src:object-tracking-cv/motion-capture] During *Game Developers Conference* 2016 in San Francisco *Epic Games* demonstrated full-body motion capture live in Unreal Engine.
[src:object-tracking-cv/motion-capture] The whole scene, from the upcoming game *Hellblade* about a woman warrior named Senua, was rendered in real-time.
[src:object-tracking-cv/motion-capture] The keynote was a collaboration between *Unreal Engine*, *Ninja Theory*, *3Lateral*, *Cubic Motion*, *IKinema* and *Xsens*.
[src:object-tracking-cv/motion-capture] In 2020, the two-time Olympic figure skating champion Yuzuru Hanyu graduated from Waseda University.
[src:object-tracking-cv/motion-capture] In his thesis, using data provided by 31 sensors placed on his body, he analysed his jumps.
[src:object-tracking-cv/motion-capture] He evaluated the use of technology both in order to improve the scoring system and to help skaters improve their jumping technique.
[src:object-tracking-cv/motion-capture] In March 2021 a summary of the thesis was published in the academic journal.
[src:object-tracking-cv/motion-capture] Motion tracking or motion capture started as a photogrammetric analysis tool in biomechanics research in the 1970s and 1980s, and expanded into education, training, sports and recently computer animation for television, cinema, and video games as the technology matured.
[src:object-tracking-cv/motion-capture] Since the 20th century, the performer has to wear markers near each joint to identify the motion by the positions or angles between the markers.
[src:object-tracking-cv/motion-capture] Acoustic, inertial, LED, magnetic or reflective markers, or combinations of any of these, are tracked, optimally at least two times the frequency rate of the desired motion.
[src:object-tracking-cv/motion-capture] The resolution of the system is important in both the spatial resolution and temporal resolution as motion blur causes almost the same problems as low resolution.
[src:object-tracking-cv/motion-capture] Since the beginning of the 21st century - and because of the rapid growth of technology - new methods have been developed.
[src:object-tracking-cv/motion-capture] Most modern systems can extract the silhouette of the performer from the background.
[src:object-tracking-cv/motion-capture] Afterwards all joint angles are calculated by fitting in a mathematical model into the silhouette.
[src:object-tracking-cv/motion-capture] For movements you can not see a change of the silhouette, there are hybrid systems available that can do both (marker and silhouette), but with less marker.
[src:object-tracking-cv/motion-capture] In robotics, some motion capture systems are based on simultaneous localization and mapping.
[src:object-tracking-cv/motion-capture] The centroid of the marker is estimated as a position within the two-dimensional image that is captured.
[src:object-tracking-cv/motion-capture] The grayscale value of each pixel can be used to provide sub-pixel accuracy by finding the centroid of the Gaussian.
[src:object-tracking-cv/motion-capture] An object with markers attached at known positions is used to calibrate the cameras and obtain their positions, and the lens distortion of each camera is measured.
[src:object-tracking-cv/motion-capture] If two calibrated cameras see a marker, a three-dimensional fix can be obtained.
[src:object-tracking-cv/motion-capture] Typically a system will consist of around 2 to 48 cameras.
[src:object-tracking-cv/motion-capture] Systems of over three hundred cameras exist to try to reduce marker swap.
[src:object-tracking-cv/motion-capture] Extra cameras are required for full coverage around the capture subject and multiple subjects.
[src:object-tracking-cv/motion-capture] Vendors have constraint software to reduce the problem of marker swapping since all passive markers appear identical.
[src:object-tracking-cv/motion-capture] Unlike active marker systems and magnetic systems, passive systems do not require the user to wear wires or electronic equipment.
[src:object-tracking-cv/motion-capture] Instead, hundreds of rubber balls are attached with reflective tape, which needs to be replaced periodically.
[src:object-tracking-cv/motion-capture] The markers are usually attached directly to the skin (as in biomechanics), or they are velcroed to a performer wearing a full-body spandex/lycra suit designed specifically for motion capture.
[src:object-tracking-cv/motion-capture] This type of system can capture large numbers of markers at frame rates usually around 120 to 160 fps although by lowering the resolution and tracking a smaller region of interest they can track as high as 10,000 fps.
[src:object-tracking-cv/motion-capture] Active optical systems triangulate positions by illuminating one LED at a time very quickly or multiple LEDs with software to identify them by their relative positions, somewhat akin to celestial navigation.
[src:object-tracking-cv/motion-capture] Rather than reflecting light back that is generated externally, the markers themselves are powered to emit their own light.
[src:object-tracking-cv/motion-capture] Since the inverse square law provides one quarter of the power at two times the distance, this can increase the distances and volume for capture.
[src:object-tracking-cv/motion-capture] This also enables a high signal-to-noise ratio, resulting in very low marker jitter and a resulting high measurement resolution (often down to 0.1 mm within the calibrated volume).
[src:object-tracking-cv/motion-capture] The TV series *Stargate SG1* produced episodes using an active optical system for the VFX allowing the actor to walk around props that would make motion capture difficult for other non-active optical systems.
[src:object-tracking-cv/motion-capture] ILM used active markers in *Van Helsing* to allow capture of Dracula's flying brides on very large sets similar to Weta's use of active markers in *Rise of the Planet of the Apes*.
[src:object-tracking-cv/motion-capture] The power to each marker can be provided sequentially in phase with the capture system providing a unique identification of each marker for a given capture frame at a cost to the resultant frame rate.
[src:object-tracking-cv/motion-capture] The ability to identify each marker in this manner is useful in real-time applications.
[src:object-tracking-cv/motion-capture] The alternative method of identifying markers is to do it algorithmically requiring extra processing of the data.
[src:object-tracking-cv/motion-capture] There are also possibilities to find the position by using colored LED markers.
[src:object-tracking-cv/motion-capture] In these systems, each color is assigned to a specific point of the body.
[src:object-tracking-cv/motion-capture] One of the earliest active marker systems in the 1980s was a hybrid passive-active mocap system with rotating mirrors and colored glass reflective markers and which used masked linear array detectors.
[src:object-tracking-cv/motion-capture] Active marker systems can further be refined by strobing one marker on at a time, or tracking multiple markers over time and modulating the amplitude or pulse width to provide marker ID.
[src:object-tracking-cv/motion-capture] 12-megapixel spatial resolution modulated systems show more subtle movements than 4-megapixel optical systems by having both higher spatial and temporal resolution.
[src:object-tracking-cv/motion-capture] Directors can see the actor's performance in real-time, and watch the results on the motion capture-driven CG character.
[src:object-tracking-cv/motion-capture] The unique marker IDs reduce the turnaround, by eliminating marker swapping and providing much cleaner data than other technologies.
[src:object-tracking-cv/motion-capture] LEDs with onboard processing and radio synchronization allow motion capture outdoors in direct sunlight while capturing at 120 to 960 frames per second due to a high-speed electronic shutter.
[src:object-tracking-cv/motion-capture] Computer processing of modulated IDs allows less hand cleanup or filtered results for lower operational costs.
[src:object-tracking-cv/motion-capture] This higher accuracy and resolution requires more processing than passive technologies, but the additional processing is done at the camera to improve resolution via subpixel or centroid processing, providing both high resolution and high speed.
[src:object-tracking-cv/motion-capture] These motion capture systems typically cost $20,000 for an eight-camera, 12-megapixel spatial resolution 120-hertz system with one actor.
[src:object-tracking-cv/motion-capture] One can reverse the traditional approach based on high-speed cameras.
[src:object-tracking-cv/motion-capture] Systems such as Prakash use inexpensive multi-LED high-speed projectors.
[src:object-tracking-cv/motion-capture] The specially built multi-LED IR projectors optically encode the space.
[src:object-tracking-cv/motion-capture] Instead of retro-reflective or active light emitting diode (LED) markers, the system uses photosensitive marker tags to decode the optical signals.
[src:object-tracking-cv/motion-capture] By attaching tags with photo sensors to scene points, the tags can compute not only their own locations of each point, but also their own orientation, incident illumination, and reflectance.
[src:object-tracking-cv/motion-capture] These tracking tags work in natural lighting conditions and can be imperceptibly embedded in attire or other objects.
[src:object-tracking-cv/motion-capture] The system supports an unlimited number of tags in a scene, with each tag uniquely identified to eliminate marker reacquisition issues.
[src:object-tracking-cv/motion-capture] Since the system eliminates a high-speed camera and the corresponding high-speed image stream, it requires significantly lower data bandwidth.
[src:object-tracking-cv/motion-capture] The tags also provide incident illumination data which can be used to match scene lighting when inserting synthetic elements.
[src:object-tracking-cv/motion-capture] The technique appears ideal for on-set motion capture or real-time broadcasting of virtual sets but has yet to be proven.
[src:object-tracking-cv/motion-capture] Motion capture technology has been available for researchers and scientists for a few decades, which has given new insight into many fields.
[src:object-tracking-cv/motion-capture] The vital part of the system, the underwater camera, has a waterproof housing.
[src:object-tracking-cv/motion-capture] The housing has a finish that withstands corrosion and chlorine which makes it perfect for use in basins and swimming pools.
[src:object-tracking-cv/motion-capture] Industrial high-speed cameras can also be used as infrared cameras.
[src:object-tracking-cv/motion-capture] Infrared underwater cameras come with a cyan light strobe instead of the typical IR light for minimum fall-off underwater and high-speed cameras with an LED light or with the option of using image processing.
[src:object-tracking-cv/motion-capture] An underwater camera is typically able to measure 15–20 meters depending on the water quality, the camera and the type of marker used.
[src:object-tracking-cv/motion-capture] Unsurprisingly, the best range is achieved when the water is clear, and like always, the measurement volume is also dependent on the number of cameras.
[src:object-tracking-cv/motion-capture] A range of underwater markers are available for different circumstances.
[src:object-tracking-cv/motion-capture] Different pools require different mountings and fixtures.
[src:object-tracking-cv/motion-capture] Therefore, all underwater motion capture systems are uniquely tailored to suit each specific pool instalment.
[src:object-tracking-cv/motion-capture] For cameras placed in the center of the pool, specially designed tripods, using suction cups, are provided.
[src:object-tracking-cv/motion-capture] Emerging techniques and research in computer vision are leading to the rapid development of the markerless approach to motion capture.
[src:object-tracking-cv/motion-capture] Markerless systems such as those developed at Stanford University, the University of Maryland, MIT, and the Max Planck Institute, do not require subjects to wear special equipment for tracking.
[src:object-tracking-cv/motion-capture] Special computer algorithms are designed to allow the system to analyze multiple streams of optical input and identify human forms, breaking them down into constituent parts for tracking.
[src:object-tracking-cv/motion-capture] Traditionally markerless optical motion tracking is used to keep track of various objects, including airplanes, launch vehicles, missiles and satellites.
[src:object-tracking-cv/motion-capture] Many such optical motion tracking applications occur outdoors, requiring differing lens and camera configurations.
[src:object-tracking-cv/motion-capture] High-resolution images of the target being tracked can thereby provide more information than just motion data.
[src:object-tracking-cv/motion-capture] The image obtained from NASA's long-range tracking system on the space shuttle Challenger's fatal launch provided crucial evidence about the cause of the accident.
[src:object-tracking-cv/motion-capture] Optical tracking systems are also used to identify known spacecraft and space debris despite the fact that it has a disadvantage compared to radar in that the objects must be reflecting or emitting sufficient light.
[src:object-tracking-cv/motion-capture] An optical tracking system typically consists of three subsystems: the optical imaging system, the mechanical tracking platform and the tracking computer.
[src:object-tracking-cv/motion-capture] The optical imaging system is responsible for converting the light from the target area into a digital image that the tracking computer can process.
[src:object-tracking-cv/motion-capture] Depending on the design of the optical tracking system, the optical imaging system can vary from as simple as a standard digital camera to as specialized as an astronomical telescope on the top of a mountain.
[src:object-tracking-cv/motion-capture] The specification of the optical imaging system determines the upper limit of the effective range of the tracking system.
[src:object-tracking-cv/motion-capture] The mechanical tracking platform holds the optical imaging system and is responsible for manipulating the optical imaging system in such a way that it always points to the target being tracked.
[src:object-tracking-cv/motion-capture] The dynamics of the mechanical tracking platform combined with the optical imaging system determines the tracking system's ability to keep the lock on a target that changes speed rapidly.
[src:object-tracking-cv/motion-capture] The tracking computer is responsible for capturing the images from the optical imaging system, analyzing the image to extract the target position and controlling the mechanical tracking platform to follow the target.
[src:object-tracking-cv/motion-capture] First, the tracking computer has to be able to capture the image at a relatively high frame rate.
[src:object-tracking-cv/motion-capture] This posts a requirement on the bandwidth of the image-capturing hardware.
[src:object-tracking-cv/motion-capture] The second challenge is that the image processing software has to be able to extract the target image from its background and calculate its position.
[src:object-tracking-cv/motion-capture] Several textbook image-processing algorithms are designed for this task.
[src:object-tracking-cv/motion-capture] This problem can be simplified if the tracking system can expect certain characteristics that is common in all the targets it will track.
[src:object-tracking-cv/motion-capture] The next problem down the line is controlling the tracking platform to follow the target.
[src:object-tracking-cv/motion-capture] This is a typical control system design problem rather than a challenge, which involves modeling the system dynamics and designing controllers to control it.
[src:object-tracking-cv/motion-capture] This will however become a challenge if the tracking platform the system has to work with is not designed for real-time.
[src:object-tracking-cv/motion-capture] The software that runs such systems is also customized for the corresponding hardware components.
[src:object-tracking-cv/motion-capture] One example of such software is OpticTracker, which controls computerized telescopes to track moving objects at great distances, such as planes and satellites.
[src:object-tracking-cv/motion-capture] Another option is the software SimiShape, which can also be used hybrid in combination with markers.
[src:object-tracking-cv/motion-capture] RGB-D cameras such as Kinect capture both the color and depth images.
[src:object-tracking-cv/motion-capture] By fusing the two images, 3D colored voxels can be captured, allowing motion capture of 3D human motion and human surface in real-time.
[src:object-tracking-cv/motion-capture] Because of the use of a single-view camera, motions captured are usually noisy.
[src:object-tracking-cv/motion-capture] Machine learning techniques have been proposed to automatically reconstruct such noisy motions into higher quality ones, using methods such as lazy learning and Gaussian models.
[src:object-tracking-cv/motion-capture] Such method generates accurate enough motion for serious applications like ergonomic assessment.
[src:object-tracking-cv/motion-capture] Inertial motion capture technology is based on miniature inertial sensors, biomechanical models and sensor fusion algorithms.
[src:object-tracking-cv/motion-capture] The motion data of the inertial sensors (inertial guidance system) is often transmitted wirelessly to a computer, where the motion is recorded or viewed.
[src:object-tracking-cv/motion-capture] Most inertial systems use inertial measurement units (IMUs) containing a combination of gyroscope, magnetometer, and accelerometer, to measure rotational rates.
[src:object-tracking-cv/motion-capture] These rotations are translated to a skeleton in the software.
[src:object-tracking-cv/motion-capture] Much like optical markers, the more IMU sensors the more natural the data.
[src:object-tracking-cv/motion-capture] No external cameras, emitters or markers are needed for relative motions, although they are required to give the absolute position of the user if desired.
[src:object-tracking-cv/motion-capture] Inertial motion capture systems capture the full six degrees of freedom body motion of a human in real-time and can give limited direction information if they include a magnetic bearing sensor, although these are much lower resolution and susceptible to electromagnetic noise.
[src:object-tracking-cv/motion-capture] Benefits of using Inertial systems include: capturing in a variety of environments including tight spaces, no solving, portability, and large capture areas.
[src:object-tracking-cv/motion-capture] Disadvantages include lower positional accuracy and positional drift which can compound over time.
[src:object-tracking-cv/motion-capture] These systems are similar to the Wii controllers but are more sensitive and have greater resolution and update rates.
[src:object-tracking-cv/motion-capture] They can accurately measure the direction to the ground to within a degree.
[src:object-tracking-cv/motion-capture] The popularity of inertial systems is rising amongst game developers, mainly because of the quick and easy setup resulting in a fast pipeline.
[src:object-tracking-cv/motion-capture] A range of suits are now available from various manufacturers and base prices range from $1000 to US$80,000.
[src:object-tracking-cv/motion-capture] Mechanical motion capture systems directly track body joint angles and are often referred to as exoskeleton motion capture systems, due to the way the sensors are attached to the body.
[src:object-tracking-cv/motion-capture] A performer attaches the skeletal-like structure to their body and as they move so do the articulated mechanical parts, measuring the performer's relative motion.
[src:object-tracking-cv/motion-capture] Mechanical motion capture systems are real-time, relatively low-cost, free from occlusion, and wireless (untethered) systems that have unlimited capture volume.
[src:object-tracking-cv/motion-capture] Typically, they are rigid structures of jointed, straight metal or plastic rods linked together with potentiometers that articulate at the joints of the body.
[src:object-tracking-cv/motion-capture] These suits tend to be in the $25,000 to $75,000 range plus an external absolute positioning system.
[src:object-tracking-cv/motion-capture] Some suits provide limited force feedback or haptic input.
[src:object-tracking-cv/motion-capture] Magnetic systems calculate position and orientation by the relative magnetic flux of three orthogonal coils on both the transmitter and each receiver.
[src:object-tracking-cv/motion-capture] The relative intensity of the voltage or current of the three coils allows these systems to calculate both range and orientation by meticulously mapping the tracking volume.
[src:object-tracking-cv/motion-capture] The sensor output is six degrees of freedom (6DOF), which provides useful results obtained with two-thirds the number of markers required in optical systems; one on upper arm and one on lower arm for elbow position and angle.
[src:object-tracking-cv/motion-capture] The markers are vulnerable to magnetic and electrical interference from metal objects in the environment, like rebar (steel reinforcing bars in concrete) or wiring, which affect the magnetic field, and electrical sources such as monitors, lights, cables and computers.
[src:object-tracking-cv/motion-capture] The sensor response is nonlinear, especially toward edges of the capture area.
[src:object-tracking-cv/motion-capture] The wiring from the sensors tends to preclude extreme performance movements.
[src:object-tracking-cv/motion-capture] With magnetic systems, it is possible to monitor the results of a motion capture session in real time.
[src:object-tracking-cv/motion-capture] The capture volumes for magnetic systems are dramatically smaller than they are for optical systems.
[src:object-tracking-cv/motion-capture] With the magnetic systems, there is a distinction between alternating-current (AC) and direct-current (DC) systems: DC system uses square pulses, AC systems use sine waves.
[src:object-tracking-cv/motion-capture] Stretch sensors are flexible parallel plate capacitors that measure either stretch, bend, shear, or pressure and are typically produced from silicone.
[src:object-tracking-cv/motion-capture] When the sensor stretches or squeezes its capacitance value changes.
[src:object-tracking-cv/motion-capture] This data can be transmitted via Bluetooth or direct input and used to detect minute changes in body motion.
[src:object-tracking-cv/motion-capture] Stretch sensors are unaffected by magnetic interference and are free from occlusion.
[src:object-tracking-cv/motion-capture] The stretchable nature of the sensors also means they do not suffer from positional drift, which is common with inertial systems.
[src:object-tracking-cv/motion-capture] Stretchable sensors, on the other hands, due to the material properties of their substrates and conducting materials, suffer from relatively low signal-to-noise ratio, requiring filtering or machine learning to make them usable for motion capture.
[src:object-tracking-cv/motion-capture] These solutions result in higher latency when compared to alternative sensors.
[src:object-tracking-cv/motion-capture] Most traditional motion capture hardware vendors provide for some type of low-resolution facial capture utilizing anywhere from 32 to 300 markers with either an active or passive marker system.
[src:object-tracking-cv/motion-capture] All of these solutions are limited by the time it takes to apply the markers, calibrate the positions and process the data.
[src:object-tracking-cv/motion-capture] Ultimately the technology also limits their resolution and raw output quality levels.
[src:object-tracking-cv/motion-capture] High-fidelity facial motion capture, also known as **performance capture**, is the next generation of fidelity and is utilized to record the more complex movements in a human face in order to capture higher degrees of emotion.
[src:object-tracking-cv/motion-capture] Facial capture is currently arranging itself in several distinct camps, including traditional motion capture data, blend-shaped based solutions, capturing the actual topology of an actor's face, and proprietary systems.
[src:object-tracking-cv/motion-capture] These techniques tend to be only limited in feature resolution by the camera resolution, apparent object size and number of cameras.
[src:object-tracking-cv/motion-capture] If the user's face is 50 percent of the working area of the camera and a camera has megapixel resolution, then sub millimeter facial motions can be detected by comparing frames.
[src:object-tracking-cv/motion-capture] Recent work is focusing on increasing the frame rates and doing optical flow to allow the motions to be retargeted to other computer generated faces, rather than just making a 3D Mesh of the actor and their expressions.
[src:object-tracking-cv/motion-capture] Radio frequency positioning systems are becoming more viable as higher frequency radio frequency devices allow greater precision than older technologies such as radar.
[src:object-tracking-cv/motion-capture] The speed of light is 30 centimeters per nanosecond (billionth of a second), so a 10 gigahertz (billion cycles per second) radio frequency signal enables an accuracy of about 3 centimeters.
[src:object-tracking-cv/motion-capture] By measuring amplitude to a quarter wavelength, it is possible to improve the resolution down to about 8 mm.
[src:object-tracking-cv/motion-capture] To achieve the resolution of optical systems, frequencies of 50 gigahertz or higher are needed, which are almost as dependent on line of sight and as easy to block as optical systems.
[src:object-tracking-cv/motion-capture] Multipath and reradiation of the signal are likely to cause additional problems, but these technologies will be ideal for tracking larger volumes with reasonable accuracy, since the required resolution at 100 meter distances is not likely to be as high.
[src:object-tracking-cv/motion-capture] Many scientists believe that radio frequency will never produce the accuracy required for motion capture.
[src:object-tracking-cv/motion-capture] Researchers at Massachusetts Institute of Technology researchers said in 2015 that they had made a system that tracks motion by radio frequency signals.
[src:object-tracking-cv/motion-capture] An alternative approach was developed where the actor is given an unlimited walking area through the use of a rotating sphere, similar to a hamster ball, which contains internal sensors recording the angular movements, removing the need for external cameras and other equipment.
[src:object-tracking-cv/motion-capture] Even though this technology could potentially lead to much lower costs for motion capture, the basic sphere is only capable of recording a single continuous direction.
[src:object-tracking-cv/motion-capture] Additional sensors worn on the person would be needed to record anything more.
[src:object-tracking-cv/motion-capture] Another alternative is using a 6DOF (Degrees of freedom) motion platform with an integrated omni-directional treadmill with high resolution optical motion capture to achieve the same effect.
[src:object-tracking-cv/motion-capture] The captured person can walk in an unlimited area, negotiating different uneven terrains.
[src:object-tracking-cv/motion-capture] Applications include medical rehabilitation for balance training, bio-mechanical research and virtual reality.
[src:object-tracking-cv/motion-capture] In 3D pose estimation, an actor's pose can be reconstructed from an image or depth map.
[src:object-tracking-cv/object-detection] It is widely used in computer vision tasks such as image annotation, vehicle counting, activity recognition, face detection, face recognition, video object co-segmentation.
[src:object-tracking-cv/object-detection] It is also used in tracking objects, for example tracking a ball during a football match, tracking movement of a cricket bat, or tracking a person in a video.
[src:object-tracking-cv/object-detection] Often, the test images are sampled from a different data distribution, making the object detection task significantly more difficult.
[src:object-tracking-cv/object-detection] To address the challenges caused by the domain gap between training and test data, many unsupervised domain adaptation approaches have been proposed.
[src:object-tracking-cv/object-detection] A simple and straightforward solution for reducing the domain gap is to apply an image-to-image translation approach, such as cycle-GAN.
[src:object-tracking-cv/object-detection] Among other uses, cross-domain object detection is applied in autonomous driving, where models can be trained on a vast amount of video game scenes, since the labels can be generated without manual labor.
[src:object-tracking-cv/object-detection] Every object class has its own special features that help in classifying the class – for example all circles are round.
[src:object-tracking-cv/object-detection] Object class detection uses these special features.
[src:object-tracking-cv/object-detection] For example, when looking for circles, objects that are at a particular distance from a point (i.e. the center) are sought.
[src:object-tracking-cv/object-detection] Similarly, when looking for squares, objects that are perpendicular at corners and have equal side lengths are needed.
[src:object-tracking-cv/object-detection] A similar approach is used for face identification where eyes, nose, and lips can be found and features like skin color and distance between eyes can be found.
[src:object-tracking-cv/object-detection] For object localization, true positive is often measured by the thresholded intersection over union.
[src:object-tracking-cv/object-detection] For example, if there is a traffic sign in the image, with a bounding box drawn by a human ("ground truth label"), then a neural network has detected the traffic sign (a **true positive**) at 0.5 threshold if it has drawn a bounding box whose IoU with the ground truth is above 0.5.
[src:object-tracking-cv/object-detection] Otherwise, the bounding box is a **false positive**.
[src:object-tracking-cv/object-detection] If there is only a single ground truth bounding box, but multiple predictions, then the IoU of each prediction is calculated.
[src:object-tracking-cv/object-detection] The prediction with the highest IoU is a true positive if it is above threshold, else it is a false positive.
[src:object-tracking-cv/object-detection] All other predicted bounding boxes are false positives.
[src:object-tracking-cv/object-detection] If there is no prediction with an IoU above the threshold, then the ground truth label has a **false negative**.
[src:object-tracking-cv/object-detection] For simultaneous object localization and classification, a true positive is one where the class label is correct, and the bounding box has an IoU exceeding the threshold.
[src:object-tracking-cv/object-detection] Simultaneous object localization and classification is benchmarked by the **mean average precision** (mAP).
[src:object-tracking-cv/object-detection] The average precision (AP) of the network for a class of objects is the area under the precision-recall curve as the confidence threshold is varied.
[src:object-tracking-cv/object-detection] The mAP is the average of AP over all classes.
[src:object-tracking-cv/object-detection] However, the instance of a ring textured sea urchin creates a weakly weighted association between them.
[src:object-tracking-cv/object-detection] Methods for object detection generally fall into either neural network-based or non-neural approaches.
[src:object-tracking-cv/object-detection] For non-neural approaches, it becomes necessary to first define features using one of the methods below, then using a technique such as support vector machine (SVM) to do the classification.
[src:object-tracking-cv/object-detection] On the other hand, neural techniques are able to do end-to-end object detection without specifically defining features, and are typically based on convolutional neural networks (CNN).
[src:object-tracking-cv/optical-flow] The concept of optic flow has roots as far back as Euclid's *Optics*, but its modern formulation arose from Second World War research into pilot vision during landing.
[src:object-tracking-cv/optical-flow] Several researchers arrived at the idea independently; James J.
[src:object-tracking-cv/optical-flow] Gibson gave it its most influential treatment, publishing his theory in 1947 and created the term "optic flow" in 1950.
[src:object-tracking-cv/optical-flow] Optical flow can be estimated in a number of ways.
[src:object-tracking-cv/optical-flow] Many classical models use the intuitive assumption of *brightness constancy*; that even if a point moves between frames, its brightness stays constant.
[src:object-tracking-cv/optical-flow] To formalise this intuitive assumption, consider two consecutive frames from a video sequence, with intensity $I(x,y,t)$ , where $(x,y)$ refer to pixel coordinates and t refers to time.
[src:object-tracking-cv/optical-flow] where $\mathbf {w$ is the displacement vector between a point in the first frame and the corresponding point in the second frame.
[src:object-tracking-cv/optical-flow] By itself, the brightness constancy constraint cannot be solved for u and v at each pixel, since there is only one equation and two unknowns.
[src:object-tracking-cv/optical-flow] This is known as the *aperture problem*.
[src:object-tracking-cv/optical-flow] Therefore, additional constraints must be imposed to estimate the flow field.
[src:object-tracking-cv/optical-flow] Perhaps the most natural approach to addressing the aperture problem is to apply a smoothness constraint or a *regularization constraint* to the flow field.
[src:object-tracking-cv/optical-flow] where $\Omega$ is the extent of the images $I(x,y)$ , $\nabla$ is the gradient operator, $\alpha$ is a constant, and $\Psi ()$ is a loss function.
[src:object-tracking-cv/optical-flow] This optimisation problem is difficult to solve owing to its non-linearity.
[src:object-tracking-cv/optical-flow] To address this issue, one can use a *variational approach* and linearise the brightness constancy constraint using a first order Taylor series approximation.
[src:object-tracking-cv/optical-flow] For convenience, the derivatives of the image, ${\tfrac {\partial I}{\partial x}}$ , ${\tfrac {\partial I}{\partial y}}$ and ${\tfrac {\partial I}{\partial t}}$ are often condensed to become $I_{x}$ , $I_{y}$ and $I_{t}$ .
[src:object-tracking-cv/optical-flow] For the choice of $\Psi (x)=x^{2}$ , this method is the same as the Horn-Schunck method.
[src:object-tracking-cv/optical-flow] Of course, other choices of cost function have been used such as $\Psi (x)={\sqrt {x^{2}+\epsilon ^{2}}}$ , which is a differentiable variant of the $L^{1}$ norm.
[src:object-tracking-cv/optical-flow] To solve the aforementioned optimization problem, one can use the Euler-Lagrange equations to provide a system of partial differential equations for each point in $I(x,y,t)$ .
[src:object-tracking-cv/optical-flow] Since the image data is made up of discrete pixels, these equations are discretised.
[src:object-tracking-cv/optical-flow] Doing so yields a system of linear equations which can be solved for $(u,v)$ at each pixel, using an iterative scheme such as Gauss-Seidel.
[src:object-tracking-cv/optical-flow] Although, linearising the brightness constancy constraint simplifies the optimisation problem significantly, the linearisation is only valid for small displacements and/or smooth images.
[src:object-tracking-cv/optical-flow] To avoid this problem, a multi-scale or coarse-to-fine approach is often used.
[src:object-tracking-cv/optical-flow] In such a scheme, the images are initially downsampled and the linearised Euler-Lagrange equations are solved at the reduced resolution.
[src:object-tracking-cv/optical-flow] The estimated flow field at this scale is then used to initialise the process at next scale.
[src:object-tracking-cv/optical-flow] This initialisation process is often performed by warping one frame using the current estimate of flow field so that it is as similar to other as possible.
[src:object-tracking-cv/optical-flow] An alternate approach is to discretize the optimisation problem and then perform a search of the possible $(u,v)$ values without linearising it.
[src:object-tracking-cv/optical-flow] This search is often performed using Max-flow min-cut theorem algorithms, linear programming or belief propagation methods.
[src:object-tracking-cv/optical-flow] These regularized methods typically require manual tuning of the Lagrange multiplier, the so-called regularization parameters.
[src:object-tracking-cv/optical-flow] There has been some progress in the automatic determination of these parameters in the context of optical flow applied to particle image velocimetry (PIV) data.
[src:object-tracking-cv/optical-flow] Instead of applying the regularization constraint on a point by point basis as per a regularized model, one can group pixels into regions and estimate the motion of these regions.
[src:object-tracking-cv/optical-flow] This is known as a *parametric model*, since the motion of these regions is parameterized.
[src:object-tracking-cv/optical-flow] In formulating optical flow estimation in this way, one makes the assumption that the motion field in each region be fully characterised by a set of parameters.
[src:object-tracking-cv/optical-flow] The simplest parametric model is the Lucas-Kanade method.
[src:object-tracking-cv/optical-flow] This uses rectangular regions and parameterises the motion as purely translational.
[src:object-tracking-cv/optical-flow] The Lucas-Kanade method uses the original brightness constancy constraint as the data cost term and selects $g(x,y)=1$ .
[src:object-tracking-cv/optical-flow] Other possible local loss functions include the negative normalized cross-correlation between the two frames.
[src:object-tracking-cv/optical-flow] Instead of seeking to model optical flow directly, one can train a machine learning system to estimate optical flow.
[src:object-tracking-cv/optical-flow] Since 2015, when FlowNet was proposed, learning based models have been applied to optical flow and have gained prominence.
[src:object-tracking-cv/optical-flow] However, with the advent of transformer architecture in 2017, transformer based models have gained prominence.
[src:object-tracking-cv/optical-flow] A significant shift occurred with the introduction of RAFT (Recurrent All-Pairs Field Transforms), which replaced coarse-to-fine pyramids with a single GRU-based state that iteratively updates the flow field.
[src:object-tracking-cv/optical-flow] By maintaining a constant feature resolution at 1/8 of the input, RAFT significantly improved the preservation of fine details and robustness to fast motion compared to previous bottleneck-heavy designs, influencing a wide range of subsequent models that adopt similar iterative update mechanisms.
[src:object-tracking-cv/optical-flow] However, the all-pairs correlation used in such models is computationally expensive; for high-resolution content like FullHD or 4K, global matching can require more than 32 GB of VRAM, making it impractical for consumer-grade GPUs.
[src:object-tracking-cv/optical-flow] To address this, efficiency-focused methods such as Flow1D, MeFlow, and Memfof have been developed.
[src:object-tracking-cv/optical-flow] While these approaches generally optimize memory usage by decomposing the 2D search space, the latter optimizes correlation volumes for high-resolution multi-frame sequences, providing a practical implementation for standard GPUs.
[src:object-tracking-cv/optical-flow] Most learning-based approaches to optical flow use supervised learning.
[src:object-tracking-cv/optical-flow] In this case, many frame pairs of video data and their corresponding ground-truth flow fields are used to optimise the parameters of the learning-based model to accurately estimate optical flow.
[src:object-tracking-cv/optical-flow] This process often relies on vast synthetic training datasets, such as FlyingChairs and FlyingThings3D, due to the number of parameters involved.
[src:object-tracking-cv/optical-flow] The models are then evaluated on benchmarks like MPI Sintel, KITTI, and the high-resolution Spring dataset.
[src:object-tracking-cv/optical-flow] However, models trained exclusively on synthetic data often struggle with the domain gap when applied to real-world footage.
[src:object-tracking-cv/optical-flow] To address this, some learning-based optical flow approaches use self-supervised learning (sometimes called unsupervised learning) to reduce the need for large datasets with ground-truth data and leverage real-world footage without labels during training.
[src:object-tracking-cv/optical-flow] Instead of training models to minimise the differences between estimated and ground-truth flow fields, they are trained to achieve learning objectives such as brightness constancy and smoothness of the flow field.
[src:object-tracking-cv/optical-flow] More recently, methods like CroCo have introduced cross-view completion pre-training.
[src:object-tracking-cv/optical-flow] Forcing the network to predict the masked regions of one image using the full second image teaches the model a strong geometric understanding and better generalization than models trained solely on task-specific labels.
[src:object-tracking-cv/optical-flow] Motion estimation and video compression have developed as a major aspect of optical flow research.
[src:object-tracking-cv/optical-flow] Optical flow was used by robotics researchers in many areas such as: object detection and tracking, image dominant plane extraction, movement detection, robot navigation and visual odometry.
[src:object-tracking-cv/optical-flow] Optical flow information has been recognized as being useful for controlling micro air vehicles.
[src:object-tracking-cv/optical-flow] The application of optical flow includes the problem of inferring not only the motion of the observer and objects in the scene, but also the structure of objects and the environment.
[src:object-tracking-cv/optical-flow] Since awareness of motion and the generation of mental maps of the structure of our environment are critical components of animal (and human) vision, the conversion of this innate ability to a computer capability is similarly crucial in the field of machine vision.
[src:object-tracking-cv/optical-flow] Consider a five-frame clip of a ball moving from the bottom left of a field of vision, to the top right.
[src:object-tracking-cv/optical-flow] Motion estimation techniques can determine that on a two dimensional plane the ball is moving up and to the right and vectors describing this motion can be extracted from the sequence of frames.
[src:object-tracking-cv/optical-flow] For the purposes of video compression (e.g., MPEG), the sequence is now described as well as it needs to be.
[src:object-tracking-cv/optical-flow] However, in the field of machine vision, the question of whether the ball is moving to the right or if the observer is moving to the left is unknowable yet critical information.
[src:object-tracking-cv/optical-flow] Not even if a static, patterned background were present in the five frames, could we confidently state that the ball was moving to the right, because the pattern might have an infinite distance to the observer.
[src:object-tracking-cv/optical-flow] Optical flow has also been applied to fluid mechanics as a method of estimating flow patterns in a non-invasive way if visible tracer particles are added.
[src:object-tracking-cv/optical-flow] This approach is called particle image velocimetry (PIV).
[src:object-tracking-cv/optical-flow] It has been shown that optical flow methods can provide higher accuracy than traditional cross-correlation in PIV processing .
[src:object-tracking-cv/optical-flow] Various configurations of optical flow sensors exist.
[src:object-tracking-cv/optical-flow] One configuration is an image sensor chip connected to a processor programmed to run an optical flow algorithm.
[src:object-tracking-cv/optical-flow] Another configuration uses a vision chip, which is an integrated circuit having both the image sensor and the processor on the same die, allowing for a compact implementation.
[src:object-tracking-cv/optical-flow] An example of this is a generic optical mouse sensor used in an optical mouse.
[src:object-tracking-cv/optical-flow] In some cases the processing circuitry may be implemented using analog or mixed-signal circuits to enable fast optical flow computation using minimal current consumption.
[src:object-tracking-cv/optical-flow] One area of contemporary research is the use of neuromorphic engineering techniques to implement circuits that respond to optical flow, and thus may be appropriate for use in an optical flow sensor.
[src:object-tracking-cv/optical-flow] Such circuits may draw inspiration from biological neural circuitry that similarly responds to optical flow.
[src:object-tracking-cv/optical-flow] Optical flow sensors are used extensively in computer optical mice, as the main sensing component for measuring the motion of the mouse across a surface.
[src:object-tracking-cv/optical-flow] Optical flow sensors are also being used in robotics applications, primarily where there is a need to measure visual motion or relative motion between the robot and other objects in the vicinity of the robot.
[src:object-tracking-cv/optical-flow] The use of optical flow sensors in unmanned aerial vehicles (UAVs), for stability and obstacle avoidance, is also an area of current research.
[src:object-tracking-cv/optical-flow] As early as Euclid's *Optics* note was made of the geometry underlying optic flow.
[src:object-tracking-cv/optical-flow] Helmholtz's nineteenth-century account of motion parallax also implicitly concerns it.
[src:object-tracking-cv/optical-flow] However, its explicit identification arose during the Second World War due the need to understand how pilots judge height and direction during landing.
[src:object-tracking-cv/optical-flow] MacCurdy, in advise to the Royal Air Force in the late 1920s, had earlier observed that during a straight descent the point on the ground being approached stays fixed in the pilot's visual field while all other points appear to stream away from it.
[src:object-tracking-cv/optical-flow] Grindley, in a classified 1942 report then mathematically analyzed how retinal velocity changed during self-motion to enable an individual to accurately estimate visual speed.
[src:object-tracking-cv/optical-flow] He, however, considered only this as a cue to altitude and not information to determine travel.
[src:object-tracking-cv/optical-flow] Army Air Forces, first identified that retinal velocities radiate from a "focus of expansion" in the direction of travel.
[src:object-tracking-cv/optical-flow] Moreover, that eye movements do not disturb this, and that it was the global pattern—not individual velocities—that provided this information.
[src:object-tracking-cv/optical-flow] In 1947, he published the theory, and in 1950 gave the phenomenon the name "optic flow".
[src:object-tracking-cv/optical-flow] In 1955, he together with Paul Olum and Frank Rosenblatt detailed its mathematics.
[src:object-tracking-cv/optical-flow] Calvert at the Royal Aircraft Establishment came to a similar ideas when researching on airport approach lighting.
[src:object-tracking-cv/optical-flow] In 1949, he proposed them as the "parafoveal streamer theory" which described how pilots use the pattern and speed of visual streamers to control their descent.
[src:object-tracking-cv/optical-flow] Gibson stressed the importance of optic flow for affordance perception, the ability to discern possibilities for action within the environment.
[src:object-tracking-cv/optical-flow] Followers of Gibson and his ecological approach to psychology have further demonstrated the role of the optical flow stimulus for the perception of movement by the observer in the world; perception of the shape, distance and movement of objects in the world; and the control of locomotion.
[src:object-tracking-cv/video-tracking] The objective of video tracking is to associate target objects in consecutive video frames.
[src:object-tracking-cv/video-tracking] The association can be especially difficult when the objects are moving fast relative to the frame rate.
[src:object-tracking-cv/video-tracking] Another situation that increases the complexity of the problem is when the tracked object changes orientation over time.
[src:object-tracking-cv/video-tracking] For these situations video tracking systems usually employ a motion model which describes how the image of the target might change for different possible motions of the object.
[src:object-tracking-cv/video-tracking] To perform video tracking an algorithm analyzes sequential video frames and outputs the movement of targets between the frames.
[src:object-tracking-cv/video-tracking] There are a variety of algorithms, each having strengths and weaknesses.
[src:object-tracking-cv/video-tracking] Considering the intended use is important when choosing which algorithm to use.
[src:object-tracking-cv/video-tracking] There are two major components of a visual tracking system: target representation and localization, as well as filtering and data association.
